{"title_page": "Sanjay Dutt", "text_new": "{{About|the actor|the professional wrestler|Sonjay Dutt}}\n{{short description|Indian actor and film producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sanjay Dutt\n| image              = Sanjay Dutt at Mumbai Airport, 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| alt                = Dutt posing for the camera in a black T-shirt, also carrying a strap bag\n| caption            = Dutt in 2018\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1959|07|29}}<!--Please do not change the date without providing sources to support it.-->\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Bombay State]], India (now [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India)\n| birth_name         = Sanjay Balraj Dutt\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|Film producer}}\n| education          = [[The Lawrence School, Sanawar]]\n| parents            = [[Sunil Dutt]]<br/>[[Nargis Dutt]]\n| relatives          = See [[List of Hindi film clans#Dutt family (of Sunil Dutt)|Dutt family]]\n| years_active       = 1981\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Richa Sharma (actress)|Richa Sharma]]<br />|1987|1996|end=d.}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Rhea Pillai]]<br />|1998|2008|end=div.}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-would-love-to-write-my-biography-Sanjay-Dutt/articleshow/11860665.cms |title= I would love to write my biography: Sanjay Dutt |publisher= [[The Times of India]] |date= 13 February 2012 |accessdate= 3 October 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151215054943/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-would-love-to-write-my-biography-Sanjay-Dutt/articleshow/11860665.cms |archive-date= 15 December 2015 |url-status=live |df= dmy-all }}</ref><br/>{{marriage|[[Manyata Dutt]]<br />|2008}}\n| children           = 3\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Sanjay Dutt|Full list]]\n}}\n\n'''Sanjay Balraj Dutt'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sanjay-dutt |title=Sanjay Dutt |access-date=28 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028231147/https://www.indiatoday.in/sanjay-dutt |archive-date=28 October 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/mad-genius/sanjay-dutt-1260802|title=Sanjay Dutt|date=2016-07-29|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref> is an Indian actor, author and film producer who works in [[Bollywood|Hindi films]]. He is the recipient of [[List of awards and nominations received by Sanjay Dutt|several awards]], including two [[Filmfare Awards]] and three [[Screen Awards]]. Dutt has appeared in 187 films, ranging from romance to comedy genres, but is usually [[Typecasting (acting)|typecasted]] in action genres.\n\nThe son of actors [[Sunil Dutt]] and [[Nargis]], Dutt made his acting debut in ''[[Rocky (1981 film)|Rocky]]'' (1981), which was directed by his father. The crime thriller ''[[Naam (1986 film)|Naam]]'' (1985) proved to be a turning point in his career, which was followed by a series of commercially successful films in that decade, including ''[[Jeete Hain Shaan Se]]'' (1988), ''[[Mardon Wali Baat]]'' (1988), ''[[Ilaaka]]'' (1989), ''[[Hum Bhi Insaan Hain (1989 film)|Hum Bhi Insaan Hain]]'' (1989) and ''[[Kanoon Apna Apna]]'' (1989). He earned nominations for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor]] for ''[[Saajan]]'' (1991) and ''[[Khalnayak]]'' (1993). Dutt earned his first Best Actor at the ceremony for playing a common man-turned-gangster in ''[[Vaastav: The Reality]]'' (1999). Along with ''Vaastav: The Reality'', he also won accolades for playing an army officer in ''[[Mission Kashmir]]'' (2001), a soft-hearted goofy gangster in ''[[Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.]]'' (2003) and its sequel ''[[Lage Raho Munna Bhai]]'' (2006).\n\nDutt was arrested under the [[Terrorist and Disruptive Activities (Prevention) Act|TADA]] and the [[Arms Act, 1959|Arms Act]] in April 1993 and was convicted for violation of Arms Act for possession of illegal weapons procured from other accused in the [[1993 Bombay bombings]]. After serving his sentence, he was released in 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/from-arrest-to-release-a-complete-23-year-long-sanjay-dutt-timeline/story-7lEBOzaghF8UDsUiwBLKyO.html | title= From arrest to release: A complete, 23-year-long Sanjay Dutt timeline| publisher=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=25 February  2016 | accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2013/03/21/world/asia/india-actor-sentenced/index.html | title=Bollywood star Sanjay Dutt ordered to prison for gun possession| publisher=[[CNN]]|date=22 March  2013 | accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-21873316 | title= Sanjay Dutt: Bollywood actor sent back to jail for 1993 Mumbai blasts| publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=21 March 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Dutt's life receives considerable media coverage in India, and in 2018, ''[[Sanju]]'', a biopic based on his life (which also saw a special appearance by him), was released to positive reviews and emerged as one of the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossers of Indian cinema]].\n\n== Early life ==\nSanjay Balraj Dutt was born in a [[Punjabis|Punjabi]] family at [[Mumbai]]. His parents were noted cinema actors [[Sunil Dutt]] (born Balraj Dutt) and [[Nargis]] (born Fatima Rashid). He has two sisters, [[Priya Dutt]] and Namrata Dutt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/No-sister-gets-along-with-her-brothers-wife-Dutt/articleshow/3997120.cms|title=No sister gets along with her brother's wife: Dutt|access-date=30 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924215354/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/No-sister-gets-along-with-her-brothers-wife-Dutt/articleshow/3997120.cms|archive-date=24 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/namrata-dutt-sanju-sanjay-dutt-5256351/|title=Namrata Dutt reacts after watching Sanju: I didn't connect with Paresh Rawal and Manisha Koirala|access-date=12 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712184632/https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/namrata-dutt-sanju-sanjay-dutt-5256351/|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His mother died in 1981, shortly before his debut film's premiere; her death is cited as the instigator of his drug abuse.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Dutt used to Drugs|url=http://www.bollywoodmantra.com/news/sanjay-dutt-drug-addiction-jail-stints-and-failed-marriages/2214/|publisher=bollywoodmantra.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927231829/http://www.bollywoodmantra.com/news/sanjay-dutt-drug-addiction-jail-stints-and-failed-marriages/2214/|archive-date=27 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> As a child actor, Dutt appeared briefly as a [[qawali]] singer in the 1972 film ''[[Reshma Aur Shera]]'', which starred his father.<ref>{{cite web|author1=PTI|title=Sanjay Dutt to do a qawwali after 41 years in Zanjeer|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/sanjay-dutt-to-do-a-qawwali-after-41-years-in-zanjeer/|website=The Indian Express|accessdate=2016-05-17|date=2 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807055352/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/sanjay-dutt-to-do-a-qawwali-after-41-years-in-zanjeer/|archive-date=7 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{See also|Sanjay Dutt filmography|List of awards and nominations received by Sanjay Dutt}}\n\n=== 1981\u20131997 ===\nDutt made his [[Bollywood]] movie debut with the box-office super hit ''[[Rocky (1981 film)|Rocky]]'' in 1981. Dutt then went on to star in ''[[Vidhaata]]'', the highest-grossing Hindi film of 1982,  along with film veterans [[Dilip Kumar]], [[Shammi Kapoor]] and [[Sanjeev Kumar]]. He also starred in movies like ''[[Main Awara Hoon]]'' (1983). In 1985 he shot ''[[Jaan Ki Baazi]]'', his first film in two years.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/sanjay-dutt-on-the-wrong-side-of-the-law/|title=Sanjay Dutt \u2013 On the wrong side of the law|date=16 May 2013|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064811/https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/sanjay-dutt-on-the-wrong-side-of-the-law/|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe 1986 film ''[[Naam (1986 film)|Naam]]'' was a turning point in Dutt's career, it was a major commercial and critical success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/44956266.cms|title=Naam: The film Kumar Gaurav made for buddy Sanjay Dutt - Times of India|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181130114445/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/44956266.cms|archive-date=30 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"thehindu.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/2000/12/08/stories/09080221.htm|title=The Hindu : Like a phoenix he rises again|newspaper=The Hindu|date=8 December 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/> Dutt appeared in successful films throughout the '80s such as ''Imaandaar'', ''[[Inaam Dus Hazaar]]'', ''[[Jeete Hain Shaan Se]]'' (1988), ''[[Mardon Wali Baat]]'' (1988), ''[[Ilaaka]]'' (1989), ''[[Hum Bhi Insaan Hain (1989 film)|Hum Bhi Insaan Hain]]'' (1989), ''[[Kanoon Apna Apna]]'' (1989) and ''[[Taaqatwar]].''<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/>\n\nHis performances in both ''[[Kabzaa]]'' (1988) and [[J. P. Dutta]]'s 1989 ''[[Hathyar (1989 film)|Hathyar]]'' were both well received by critics although both films only managed average collections at the box office.<ref name=\"stargold.in\">{{cite web|title=Sanjay received critical acclaim for Kabzaa|url=http://www.stargold.in/newsdetails.aspx?nid=4451|publisher=stargold.in|accessdate=2013-08-22}}</ref><ref name=\"stargold.in\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay received critical acclaim for Kabzaa And Hathyar|url=http://movies.addatoday.com/2012/05/about-sanjay-dutt-biography.html|publisher=movies.addatoday.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113015447/http://movies.addatoday.com/2012/05/about-sanjay-dutt-biography.html|archive-date=13 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay rece|url=http://movies.addatoday.com/2012/05/about-sanjay-dutt-biography.html|publisher=movies.addatoday.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113015447/http://movies.addatoday.com/2012/05/about-sanjay-dutt-biography.html|archive-date=13 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the late 1980s he was seen in a number of multi-starrers alongside actors like [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]], [[Mithun Chakraborty|Mithun]], [[Dharmendra]], [[Jackie Shroff]] and [[Sunny Deol]].<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/>\n\nHis successes continued in the 1990s, with films that include ''[[Tejaa]]'', ''[[Khatarnaak]]'', ''[[Zahreelay]]'', ''[[Thanedaar]]'', ''[[Khoon Ka Karz]]'', ''[[Yalgaar (India film)|Yalgaar]]'', ''[[Gumrah (1993 film)|Gumrah]]'', ''[[Sahibaan]]'' and ''[[Aatish: Feel the Fire]]''. He went on to star in some of the most era-defining Indian films of the early 1990s such as ''[[Sadak]]'', ''[[Saajan]]'' (for which he was nominated for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Filmfare Best Actor Award]]) and ''[[Khalnayak]]'', for which he earned his second Filmfare Best Actor Award nomination.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/>\n\n''[[The Hindu]]'' wrote that ''\"Sanjay's earlier films (like Naam and Sadak) got him a lot of favourable attention.\"'' and \"Saajan'' established Sanjay Dutt as the conventional soft hero.\"''<ref name=\"thehindu.com\"/>''[[Saajan]]'' was the highest-grossing [[Bollywood films of 1991#Highest grossing|Bollywood film of 1991]], and [[Sadak]] was the sixth highest grosser of 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=197&catName=MTk5MQ==|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115230117/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=197&catName=MTk5MQ==|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 January 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com|date=15 January 2013|publisher=}}</ref> ''[[Khalnayak]]'' was a box office success. The movie was the second-highest grosser of 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=199&catName=MTk5Mw==|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017072516/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=199&catName=MTk5Mw==|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 October 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com|date=17 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref> This was followed by another box office success [[Gumrah (1993 film)|''Gumrah'']], this was Dutt's second consecutive hit of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1054253/10-movies-we-couldnt-imagine-without-sanju-baba/|title=10 movies we couldn't imagine without Sanju Baba - The Express Tribune|date=21 March 2016|publisher=|access-date=9 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809121848/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1054253/10-movies-we-couldnt-imagine-without-sanju-baba/|archive-date=9 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 1997\u2013present ===\n\nDutt's first film after his 1993 arrest was ''[[Daud (film)|Daud]]'' (1997). It did not do well at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficeindia.com/years.php?year=1997&pageId=4|title=Top India Total Nett Gross 1997 - - Box Office India|website=www.boxofficeindia.com|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064750/https://www.boxofficeindia.com/years.php?year=1997&pageId=4|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He followed this with the 1998 ''[[Dushman (1998 film)|Dushman]]'' which did well at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficeindia.com/years.php?year=1998&pageId=4|title=Top India Total Nett Gross 1998 - - Box Office India|website=www.boxofficeindia.com|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064813/https://www.boxofficeindia.com/years.php?year=1998&pageId=4|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> 1999 was an excellent year for Dutt and one that is regarded as his comeback, with all of his five releases being amongst the highest-grossing films of that year. He began it by starring in the Mahesh Bhatt-directed hit ''[[Kartoos]]'', followed by ''[[Khoobsurat (1999 film)|Khoobsurat]]'', ''[[Haseena Maan Jaayegi]]'', ''[[Daag (1999 film)|Daag: The Fire]]'' and ''[[Vaastav: The Reality]]'', for which he won many awards, including his first Filmfare Best Actor Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/entertainment/bollywood/sanjay-dutt-turns-57/ss-BBpUr2p|title=Sanjay Dutt turns 57|website=www.msn.com|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709035301/https://www.msn.com/en-in/entertainment/bollywood/sanjay-dutt-turns-57/ss-BBpUr2p|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/sanjay-dutt-feels-his-cult-film-vaastav-wasn-t-good-did-you-notice-this-fact-in-sanju/250526|title=Sanjay Dutt feels his cult film Vaastav wasn't good - did you notice this fact in Sanju?|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064616/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/sanjay-dutt-feels-his-cult-film-vaastav-wasn-t-good-did-you-notice-this-fact-in-sanju/250526|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His role in 2000's ''[[Mission Kashmir]]'' won him critical acclaim and a number of awards and nominations.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/> Dutt was also invited by the President of India to [[Rashtrapati Bhavan]] for his performance in the movie.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yFAvxLLVPygC&pg=PA461&lpg=PA461&dq=just+couldn\u2019t+believe+what+was+happening+around+me.+I+was+in+a+haze.+I+was+in+a+state+of+delirium.+I+couldn\u2019t+for+the+life+of+me+believe+that+I+who+was+considered+and+is+still+considered+a+criminal#v=onepage&q=just%20couldn\u2019t%20believe%20what%20was%20happening%20around%20me.%20I%20was%20in%20a%20haze.%20I%20was%20in%20a%20state%20of%20delirium.%20I%20couldn\u2019t%20for%20the%20life%20of%20me%20believe%20that%20I%20who%20was%20considered%20and%20is%20still%20considered%20a%20criminal&f=false|title=Maximum city: Bombay lost and found|isbn=9780144001590|last1=Mehta|first1=Suketu|year=2006}}</ref>\n\nAs the decade went on, he continued to play lead roles in popular and critical successes such as ''[[Jodi No.1]]'' (2001), ''[[Pitaah]]'' (2002), ''[[Kaante]]'' (2002) and the National Award-winning film ''[[Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.]]'' (2003), which garnered him several awards.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/> At the box office ''Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.'' achieved a silver jubilee status (25-week run) being one of only eight films to have achieved this status since the year 2000. In its 26th week of release, the film could still be found playing on 257 screens throughout India.<ref name=g>{{cite web|author=|title=Top Earners 2003|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=209&catName=MjAwMw==|publisher=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=10 July 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120525225820/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=209&catName=MjAwMw==|archivedate=25 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsx.com/programmes/at-the-movies-with-anupama-chopra/at-the-movies-with-anupama-chopra-in-conversation-with-rajkumar-hirani-on-his-first-directorial-venture-munna-bhai-mbbs |title=Archived copy |access-date=19 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919094610/https://www.newsx.com/programmes/at-the-movies-with-anupama-chopra/at-the-movies-with-anupama-chopra-in-conversation-with-rajkumar-hirani-on-his-first-directorial-venture-munna-bhai-mbbs |archive-date=19 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Later successes came with ''[[Musafir (2004 film)|Musafir]]'' (2004), ''[[Plan]]'' (2004), ''[[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]]'' (2005) and ''[[Dus]]'' (2005). He won critical acclaim for his performances in ''[[Shabd (film)|Shabd]]'' (2005) and ''[[Zinda (film)|Zinda]]''.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/>\n\nThe sequel of ''Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.'', ''[[Lage Raho Munna Bhai]]'' was released in late 2006. Dutt received a number of awards for his performance in the film, along with an award from the Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] for his work in the ''Munna bhai'' series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Received award by PM|url=http://www.in.com/sanjay-dutt/biography-284.html|publisher=www.in.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113100610/http://www.in.com/sanjay-dutt/biography-284.html|archive-date=13 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[NDTV India]] counted the character ''[[Munna Bhai]]'' as one of top 20 fictional characters in Bollywood.<ref>[http://movies.ndtv.com/photos/indian-cinema-100-bollywood-s-20-best-characters-15056/slide/3 Indian cinema@100: Bollywood's 20 best characters - NDTV] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620101214/http://movies.ndtv.com/photos/indian-cinema-100-bollywood-s-20-best-characters-15056/slide/3 |date=20 June 2018 }}. [[NDTV]]. Retrieved 14 July 2014</ref> Later Dutt starred in movies like ''[[Dhamaal]]'' (2007), ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]'' (2007), ''[[All the Best: Fun Begins|All the Best]]'' (2009), ''[[Double Dhamaal]]'' (2011), ''[[Son of Sardaar]]'' (2012) ''[[Agneepath (2012 film)|Agneepath]]'' (2012) and ''[[PK (film)|PK]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.spotboye.com/bollywood/listed/looking-back-at-sanjay-dutt-s-journey/567c060817b6144b64adb15c |title=Looking Back at Sanjay Dutt's Journey |access-date=3 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903215124/https://www.spotboye.com/bollywood/listed/looking-back-at-sanjay-dutt-s-journey/567c060817b6144b64adb15c |archive-date=3 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, the Indian film Institute Filmfare listed 12 films featuring Dutt in its list of top 100 highest-grossing movies of all time. In its May 2013 edition \"100 years of Indian cinema\" Filmfare listed three films featuring Dutt in its top 20 list of highest-grossing Hindi films of all time, adjusted for inflation these films were ''Lage Raho Munna Bhai'', ''Khalnayak'' and ''Saajan''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/299794|title=#4 Key Turning Points in the Career of Bollywood's favourite Baba|first=Nidhi|last=Singh|date=7 September 2017|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064755/https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/299794|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVidhu Vinod Chopra on 29 September 2016 announced that the third part of Munna Bhai series, starring Dutt in the title role, would begin soon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/work-on-munnabhai-3-to-begin-next-year-vidhu-vinod-chopra/1/776723.html|title=Work on Munnabhai 3 to begin next year: Vidhu Vinod Chopra|website=India Today|access-date=9 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009202407/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/work-on-munnabhai-3-to-begin-next-year-vidhu-vinod-chopra/1/776723.html|archive-date=9 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, Dutt appeared as the lead in ''[[Bhoomi (film)|Bhoomi]]'', directed by [[Omung Kumar]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Omung-Kumar%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%98Bhoomi%E2%80%99-to-be-Sanjay-Dutt%E2%80%99s-comeback-film/article16668989.ece|title=Omung Kumar's 'Bhoomi' to be Sanjay Dutt's comeback film|date=20 November 2016|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|access-date=10 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214111603/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Omung-Kumar%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%98Bhoomi%E2%80%99-to-be-Sanjay-Dutt%E2%80%99s-comeback-film/article16668989.ece|archive-date=14 December 2016|url-status=live|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> In 2018, he starred in ''Saheb, Biwi Aur Gangster 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/movies-to-look-forward-to/sd/photostory/58803816.cms|title=Pic: Sanjay Dutt's new look for 'Saheb Biwi Aur Gangster 3' is menacing - Movies to look forward to {{!}} The Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909151308/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/movies-to-look-forward-to/sd/photostory/58803816.cms|archive-date=9 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/saheb-biwi-aur-gangster-3-sanjay-dutt-chitrangada-singh-begin-shooting-in-rajasthan/story-u91f4APbiAYtFzwYOaKjeK.html|title=Saheb Biwi Aur Gangster 3: Sanjay Dutt, Chitrangada Singh begin shooting in Rajasthan|date=2017-09-28|work=hindustantimes.com|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928151639/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/saheb-biwi-aur-gangster-3-sanjay-dutt-chitrangada-singh-begin-shooting-in-rajasthan/story-u91f4APbiAYtFzwYOaKjeK.html|archive-date=28 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, it was also announced that Dutt would feature alongside [[Ranbir Kapoor]] and [[Vaani Kapoor]] in ''Shamshera,'' which will release on 31 July 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yashrajfilms.com/movies/shamshera|title=Shamshera|website=www.yashrajfilms.com|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> On 29 June 2018, his biopic ''[[Sanju]]'' released in which he made a special appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/bollywood/sanjay-dutt-stars-in-sanju|title=Confirmed! Sanjay Dutt Makes an Appearance in 'Sanju'|publisher=|date=28 June 2018}}</ref> Dutt and [[Alia Bhatt]] are currently shooting for ''[[Sadak#Sequel|Sadak 2]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/confirmed-alia-bhatt-sanjay-dutt-star-mahesh-bhatts-sadak-2-exclusive-details-full-star-cast/ |title=CONFIRMED! Alia Bhatt \u2013 Sanjay Dutt to star in Mahesh Bhatt's Sadak 2 (EXCLUSIVE details on full star cast) |date=1 September 2018 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |access-date=6 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904172648/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/confirmed-alia-bhatt-sanjay-dutt-star-mahesh-bhatts-sadak-2-exclusive-details-full-star-cast/ |archive-date=4 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In 2019, he joined the cast of historical film ''Bhuj: The Pride of India'', which will feature an ensemble cast consisting of [[Ajay Devgn]], [[Sonakshi Sinha]] and [[Parineeti Chopra]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/bhuj-the-pride-of-india-sanjay-dutt-sonakshi-sinha-rana-daggubati-parineeti-chopra-and-ammy-virk-join-the-ajay-devgn-starrer/articleshow/68493083.cms|title='Bhuj: The Pride of India': Sanjay Dutt, Sonakshi Sinha, Rana Daggubati, Parineeti Chopra and Ammy Virk join the Ajay Devgn starrer - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> He will soon be seen in the film [[Prassthanam]] on 20 September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/prasthanam-teaser-sanjay-dutt-takes-no-prisoners-as-politician-in-war-of-legacy-2077177 |title = Prasthanam Teaser: Sanjay Dutt Takes No Prisoners as Politician in War of Legacy}}</ref>\n\n== Off-screen work ==\nDutt co-hosted the [[Bigg Boss 5|fifth season]] of the Indian reality show ''[[Bigg Boss]]'' along with [[Salman Khan]]. The show aired on ''Colors'' television from 2 October 2011 to 7 January 2012.<ref name=\"Sanjay Dutt, Salman to host Bigg Boss 5 together\">{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt, Salman to host Bigg Boss 5 together|url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2011/jul/200711-informer-2.htm|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=Mi Day|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123215525/http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2011/jul/200711-informer-2.htm|archive-date=23 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Dutt later said it was Khan who persuaded him to co-host the show.<ref name=\"Salman convinced me for Bigg Boss: Sanjay Dutt\">{{cite news|title=Salman convinced me for Bigg Boss: Sanjay Dutt|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Television/Salman-convinced-me-for-Bigg-Boss-Sanjay-Dutt/Article1-752439.aspx|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=Hindustan Times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106030402/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Television/salman-convinced-me-for-bigg-boss-sanjay-dutt/Article1-752439.aspx|archivedate=6 January 2012}}</ref> Dutt and entrepreneur [[Indian Premier League]] cricket team owner [[Raj Kundra]] together launched India's first professionally organised [[mixed martial arts]] league\u2014the [[Super Fight League]]\u2014on 16 January 2012.<ref name=TOI01172012>{{cite news |title=Ready for the Super Fight League? |newspaper=The Times Of India |location=Mumbai |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-17/news-interviews/30632385_1_mma-sport-fight-night |first=Roshni |last=Olivera |accessdate=2012-01-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212031726/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-17/news-interviews/30632385_1_mma-sport-fight-night |archive-date=12 December 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and media image ==\n[[File:SanjayDutt-ManyataDutt.jpg|thumb|240px|right|Dutt with wife Manyata in 2011]]\nIn the early 1980s, Dutt had a relationship with his co-star from his first film, [[Tina Ambani|Tina Munim]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodshaadis.com/articles/throwback-\nSanjay dutt best friend in dreams and his best fan is Agha Ali Sajjad Memon in the world he likes his all filmy activity amd real life activeties and  will meet sooon\ninterview-of-sanjay-dutt-about-ex-girlfriend-tina-munim-9258|title=Throwback Interview Of Sanjay Dutt About Ex-Girlfriend Tina Munim: I Am Very Possessive About Her|website=BollywoodShaadis|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> After this relationship ended, Dutt married actress [[Richa Sharma (actress)|Richa Sharma]] in 1987.<ref name=\"trib1\">{{cite web|title=I have become a family man: Sanjay Dutt|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/61609/i-have-become-a-family-man-sanjay-dutt/|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=2010-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111133252/http://tribune.com.pk/story/61609/i-have-become-a-family-man-sanjay-dutt/|archive-date=11 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> She died of a brain tumour in 1996. The couple have a daughter, Trishala, born in 1988, who lives in the United States with her maternal grandparents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/dutt/20080704.htm|title=Sanjay Dutt's tearful reunion with daughter|publisher=|access-date=10 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710041308/http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/dutt/20080704.htm|archive-date=10 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Dutt's second marriage was to air-hostess-turned-model [[Rhea Pillai]] in February 1998.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sanjay Weds |url=http://www.screenindia.com/feb27/news.htm |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010825183940/http://www.screenindia.com/feb27/news.htm |archivedate=25 August 2001}}</ref> The divorce finalised in 2008. Dutt married [[Manyata Dutt|Manyata]] (born Dilnawaz Sheikh)<ref>{{cite web|title=Unknown starlet Dilnawaz's journey to Mrs Manyata Dutt|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/unknown-starlet-dilnawazs-journey-to-mrs-manyata-dutt/83359-8.html|publisher=Ibnlive.in|accessdate=2010-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808150620/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/unknown-starlet-dilnawazs-journey-to-mrs-manyata-dutt/83359-8.html|archive-date=8 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> first registered in [[Goa]] in 2008 and then, in a [[Hindu]] ceremony in [[Mumbai]], after two years of dating.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sanjay Dutt marries Manyata |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-31876920080211 |work=Reuters |accessdate=2010-10-21 |date=11 February 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418014230/http://in.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-31876920080211 |archive-date=18 April 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref> On 21 October 2010, he became a father to twins, a boy and a girl.<ref>{{cite news|title=Manyata Dutt delivers twins |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-21/news-interviews/28247462_1_manyata-dutt-twins-trishala|work=Times of India|accessdate=2010-10-21 |date=21 October 2010}}</ref> He is a devout [[Shaivism|Shaiva]] [[Hindu]] who has read holy scriptures and theological works.<ref>[http://www.deccanchronicle.com/amp/entertainment/bollywood/210316/sanjay-dutt-to-work-for-jail-reforms-1.html/ Personal Life Material] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024044245/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/amp/entertainment/bollywood/210316/sanjay-dutt-to-work-for-jail-reforms-1.html/ |date=24 October 2017 }} - Religious Views Source</ref>\n\nBombay (now Mumbai) suffered a series of [[1993 Bombay bombings|serial bombings in 1993]]. Dutt was among several people associated with Bollywood who were accused of involvement. It was alleged that Dutt accepted a delivery of weapons at his house from [[Abu Salem]] and co-accused Riyaz Siddiqui, who had also been implicated in relation to the Mumbai blasts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=174294 |title=Charges framed against Salem|publisher=Indian Express|accessdate=2009-04-19|date=18 March 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829173254/http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=174294 |archivedate=29 August 2009}}</ref> It was claimed that the weapons formed a part of a large consignment of arms connected to the terrorists.<ref name=\"ibn\" /> Dutt, however, in his confession stated that he took only one [[Type 56 assault rifle|Type-56]] from the producers of his movie ''Sanam'', for his own family protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/1993-mumbai-blasts-sanjay-dutts-confessional-statement-598327.html|title=1993 Mumbai blasts: Sanjay Dutt's confessional statement|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064626/https://www.news18.com/news/india/1993-mumbai-blasts-sanjay-dutts-confessional-statement-598327.html|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It has also been reported that Sanjay Dutt's father [[Sunil Dutt]]'s political rivalry caused Sanjay Dutt's conviction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/reel-vs-real-the-politics-behind-the-life-and-crimes-of-sanjay-dutt-118070900115_1.html|title=Reel vs real: The politics behind the life and crimes of Sanjay Dutt|first=Rasheed|last=Kidwai|date=9 July 2018|publisher=|via=Business Standard|access-date=24 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724154341/https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/reel-vs-real-the-politics-behind-the-life-and-crimes-of-sanjay-dutt-118070900115_1.html|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1993, he was arrested under the provisions of the [[Terrorist and Disruptive Activities (Prevention) Act]] (TADA).<ref name=\"ibn\">{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sanjay-dutt-gets-6-yrs-jail-taken-into-custody/45923-4-single.html|title=Sanjay Dutt gets 6 yrs jail, taken into custody |publisher=IBN |accessdate=2009-04-19 |date=31 July 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091219154300/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sanjay-dutt-gets-6-yrs-jail-taken-into-custody/45923-4-single.html|archivedate=19 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Ryan Clarke |title=Crime-Terror Nexus in South Asia: States, Security and Non-State Actors |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQcbIfg739IC&pg=PA58|accessdate=2013-05-16|date=12 April 2011 |publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-136-73970-5|pages=58\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sanjay-dutt-gets-fiveyear-jail-term-in-1993-mumbai-blasts/1091259/ |title=Sanjay Dutt sentenced to 5 years in jail, gets 4 weeks to surrender |publisher=Indian Express |date=2013-03-22 |accessdate=2013-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323192432/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sanjay-dutt-gets-fiveyear-jail-term-in-1993-mumbai-blasts/1091259 |archive-date=23 March 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Dutt was granted bail by the [[Supreme Court of India]] on 5 May 1993; however, on 4 July 1994 his bail was cancelled and he was re-arrested. On 16 October 1995 he was granted bail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/from-arrest-to-release-a-complete-23-year-long-sanjay-dutt-timeline/story-7lEBOzaghF8UDsUiwBLKyO.html|title=From arrest to release: A complete, 23-year-long Sanjay Dutt timeline|date=25 February 2016|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064548/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/from-arrest-to-release-a-complete-23-year-long-sanjay-dutt-timeline/story-7lEBOzaghF8UDsUiwBLKyO.html|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Abdul Qayyum Abdul Karim Shaikh, who was thought to be a close aide of the terrorists' ringleader, [[Dawood Ibrahim]], was arrested.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/man-who-supplied-pistol-to-sanjay-dutt-arrested/23273/|title=Man who supplied pistol to Sanjay Dutt arrested|publisher=Indian Express|accessdate=2009-04-19|date=14 February 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829195011/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/man-who-supplied-pistol-to-sanjay-dutt-arrested/23273/|archive-date=29 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Dutt had given Qayuum's name to the police when confessing to arms possession, saying that in September 1992 he had bought a [[pistol]] from Qayuum in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/feb/13shaikh.htm|title=93 blast accused Abdul Qayyum Shaikh arrested|publisher=[[rediff.com]]|accessdate=2009-04-19|date=13 February 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090830104020/http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/feb/13shaikh.htm|archive-date=30 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2007, Dutt was cleared of the charges relating to the Mumbai blast; however, the TADA court sentenced Dutt to six years' [[rigorous imprisonment]] under Arms act for illegal possession of weapons.<ref name=\"ibn\" /><ref name=star>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/aug/01/film.india|title=Bollywood star gets six years as lengthy Mumbai bombing trial ends|author=Randeep Ramesh|newspaper=the Guardian|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231081329/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/aug/01/film.india|archive-date=31 December 2016|url-status=live|date=August 2007}}</ref> According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', \"The actor claimed he feared for his life after the notorious 'Black Friday' bombings, which were allegedly staged by Mumbai's Muslim-dominated mafia in retaliation for deadly Hindu-Muslim clashes a few months earlier. But the judge rejected this defence and also refused bail.\"<ref name=star/> Dutt was returned to jail at Arthur Road and soon after moved to the [[Yerawada Central Jail]] in [[Pune]].<ref name=\"ibn\"/><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/story.aspx?id=NEWEN20070021271 | title = Priya to approach SC for Sanju's bail | author = Imtiaz Jaleel | publisher = NDTV | date = 2 August 2007 | accessdate = 31 July 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225512/http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/story.aspx?id=NEWEN20070021271 | archivedate = 26 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Dutt appealed against the sentence<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6934560.stm|title=BBC NEWS - South Asia - Bollywood's Dutt appeals sentence|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121152918/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6934560.stm|archive-date=21 January 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> and was granted interim bail on 20 August 2007 until such time as the TADA court provided him with a copy of its judgement.<ref>[http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2007/08/20/9955/index.html Sanjay Dutt gets bail. He was biif] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829180603/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2007/08/20/9955/index.html |date=29 August 2009 }}</ref> On 22 October 2007 Dutt was back in jail but again applied for bail. On 27 November 2007, Dutt was granted bail by the Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2580913.cms|title=Sanjay Dutt released from Pune jail|work=The Times of India|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829225338/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2580913.cms|archive-date=29 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March 2013 the Supreme Court upheld the verdict but shortened the sentence to five years' imprisonment. Dutt was given a month to surrender before the authorities.<ref name=\"As it happened: I\u2019ve been a good human, says Dutt\">{{cite news|title=As it happened: I've been a good human, says Sanjay Dutt|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/as-it-happened-ive-been-a-good-human-says-sanjay-dutt-669614.html|accessdate=2013-05-17|newspaper=First Post|date=21 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526025204/http://www.firstpost.com/india/as-it-happened-ive-been-a-good-human-says-sanjay-dutt-669614.html|archive-date=26 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDutt has said that \"I am not a politician but I belong to a political family.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/topNews/idINIndia-37493320090116?sp=true |title=Sanjay Dutt to contest elections on Samajwadi Party ticket |publisher=Reuters |date=16 January 2009 |access-date=16 January 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904201406/http://in.reuters.com/article/topNews/idINIndia-37493320090116?sp=true |archive-date=4 September 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was persuaded by a close friend to contest the [[2009 Indian general election|2009 Lok Sabha elections]] as a candidate for the [[Samajwadi Party]], but withdrew when the court refused to suspend his conviction.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sanjay-dutt-cant-contest-polls-supreme-court/89121-37.html |title=Sanjay Dutt can't contest polls: Supreme Court |publisher=IBN |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016032036/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sanjay-dutt-cant-contest-polls-supreme-court/89121-37.html |archivedate=16 October 2012 |date=31 March 2009}}</ref> He was then appointed General Secretary of the Samajwadi Party, leaving that post in December 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Dutt leaves the post of Samajwadi Party|url=http://in.news.yahoo.com/sanjay-dutt-s-20-year-nightmare-094611351.html|publisher=yahoo|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005021131/http://in.news.yahoo.com/sanjay-dutt-s-20-year-nightmare-094611351.html|archive-date=5 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2013 the Supreme Court upheld Dutt's five-year sentence, 18 months of which he already spent in jail during the trial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/sanjay-dutt-convicted-in-1993-bombay-blasts-case-gets-5-years-in-jail-345095?pfrom=home-lateststories |title=Sanjay Dutt convicted in 1993 Bombay blasts case, gets 5 years in jail |publisher=NDTV.com |date=2013-03-21 |accessdate=2013-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323234256/http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/sanjay-dutt-convicted-in-1993-bombay-blasts-case-gets-5-years-in-jail-345095?pfrom=home-lateststories |archive-date=23 March 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was given four weeks to surrender to the authorities, the court having refused to release him on probation due to the severity of the offence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Dutt given 4 Weeks to surrender|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/sc-grants-4-weeks-more-to-Sanjay-Dutt-to-surrender/article4627135.ece|publisher=hindubusinessline.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230233441/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/sc-grants-4-weeks-more-to-sanjay-dutt-to-surrender/article4627135.ece|archive-date=30 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May, the Supreme Court rejected Dutt's [[review petition]] for the reconsideration of his conviction and asked him to surrender on the stipulated date.<ref>{{cite news|title=1993 Mumbai blasts case: 1993 Bombay blast case: Supreme Court dismisses Sanjay Dutt's review petition|newspaper=Economic Times|location=Mumbai|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/1993-bombay-blast-case-supreme-court-dismisses-sanjay-dutts-review-petition/articleshow/19986334.cms|access-date=10 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921124911/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/1993-bombay-blast-case-supreme-court-dismisses-sanjay-dutts-review-petition/articleshow/19986334.cms|archive-date=21 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Review plea rejected: Sanjay Dutt will have to go to Jail|url=http://southmonitor.com/2013/05/11/review-plea-rejected-sanjay-dutt-will-have-to-go-to-jail/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909031023/http://southmonitor.com/2013/05/11/review-plea-rejected-sanjay-dutt-will-have-to-go-to-jail/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-09-09|publisher=Southmonitor.com}}</ref> on 14 May, Dutt withdrew the mercy plea and surrendered to the Mumbai Police on 16 May 2013.<ref name=\"Sanjay Dutt withdraws plea, set to surrender before TADA court tomorrow\">{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt withdraws plea, set to surrender before TADA court tomorrow/1116049/?rheditorpick#sthash.mToe0p5t.dpuf|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sanjay-dutt-withdraws-plea-set-to-surrender-before-jail-tomorrow/1116049/?rheditorpick|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=Indian Express|date=16 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Sanjay Dutt reaches Tada court, will surrender shortly\">{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt reaches Tada court, will surrender shortly|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-05-16/india/39309264_1_imperial-heights-sanjay-dutt-manyata|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=The Times of India|date=16 May 2013}}</ref> Just before the surrender, the Mumbai jail authority got an anonymous letter threatening Dutt's life. Dutt filed an appeal to allow him to surrender before entering Yerwada Central Jail. Later, Dutt withdrew this request too.<ref name=\"Sanjay Dutt to surrender today, jail gets threat letter\">{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt to surrender today, jail gets threat letter|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-05-16/india/39309404_1_sanjay-dutt-yerwada-jail-letter-threat|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref> He was paroled from 21 December 2013. The parole was extended three times until March 2014, raising concern in Bombay High Court and a proposal from the [[Government of Maharashtra]] to amend the law of parole. He returned to Yerwada Central Jail after his parole ended.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt's parole over, leaves for Yerwada. In December 2014, he was out on Furlough for 14 days again.|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/sanjay-dutt-leaves-home-yerwada-jail/1/350688.html|newspaper=India Today|date=22 March 2014|accessdate=2014-05-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527221758/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/sanjay-dutt-leaves-home-yerwada-jail/1/350688.html|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Dutt was out on a two weeks' furlough granted by the Yerwada Central Jail authorities on 24 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/out-on-parole-sanjay-dutt-watches-pk-with-family-718105|title=Out on Parole, Sanjay Dutt Watches PK With Family|work=NDTVMovies.com|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226112829/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/out-on-parole-sanjay-dutt-watches-pk-with-family-718105|archive-date=26 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>  He was subsequently incarcerated in Yerwada Central Jail, to complete his jail term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sanjay-dutt-shifted-to-punes-yerawada-jail-522972|title=Sanjay Dutt shifted to Pune's Yerawada Jail|author=Rashmi Rajput|date=22 May 2013|work=NDTV.com|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518083512/http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sanjay-dutt-shifted-to-punes-yerawada-jail-522972|archive-date=18 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He was released from there on 25 February 2016 after serving his sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-35647886|title=How Bollywood star Sanjay Dutt spent his time in jail|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720080258/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-35647886|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live|date=25 February 2016|last1=Changoiwala|first1=Puja}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nA biopic film based on the life of Dutt, titled ''[[Sanju]]'', in which [[Ranbir Kapoor]] portrays the title character,<ref>{{cite news |work=Indian Express |title=Shooting for Sanjay Dutt biopic featuring Ranbir Kapoor begins, tweets Rajkummar Hirani |date=14 January 2017 |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/shooting-for-sanjay-dutt-biopic-begins-4473777/ |accessdate=2017-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115141557/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/shooting-for-sanjay-dutt-biopic-begins-4473777/ |archive-date=15 January 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> was released on 29 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/sanju-trailer-watch-drama-drugs-and-ranbir-kapoor/article24034889.ece|title='Sanju' trailer watch: drama, drugs and Ranbir Kapoor|last=Desk|first=The Hindu Net|date=2018-05-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-05-30|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/sanju-trailer-heres-how-bollywood-is-applauding-ranbir-kapoor-for-his-performance/articleshow/64383711.cms|title=Sanju Trailer: Here's how Bollywood is applauding Ranbir Kapoor for his performance|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-05-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530175645/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/sanju-trailer-heres-how-bollywood-is-applauding-ranbir-kapoor-for-his-performance/articleshow/64383711.cms|archive-date=30 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box|viaf=64240660}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0004569}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrity/sanjay-dutt/ Sanjay Dutt] at [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n{{Sanjay Dutt}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Sanjay Dutt\n| list =\n{{FilmfareAwardBestActor 1981-2000}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestComedian}}\n{{ScreenAwardBestActor}}\n{{ScreenAwardBestSupportingActor}}\n{{StardustAwardMaleStar}}\n{{ZeeCineAwardBestActorMale}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dutt, Sanjay}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Indian male child actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male singers]]\n[[Category:Lawrence School, Sanawar alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Samajwadi Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian actor-politicians]]\n[[Category:Bigg Boss]]\n[[Category:Indian game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Paroled people]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male comedians]]\n[[Category:Hindi film producers]]\n[[Category:Indian criminals]]\n[[Category:Sanjay Dutt]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the actor|the professional wrestler|Sonjay Dutt}}\n{{short description|Indian actor and film producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sanjay Dutt\n| image              = Sanjay Dutt at Mumbai Airport, 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| alt                = Dutt posing for the camera in a black T-shirt, also carrying a strap bag\n| caption            = Dutt in 2018\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1959|07|29}}<!--Please do not change the date without providing sources to support it.-->\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Bombay State]], India (now [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India)\n| birth_name         = Sanjay Balraj Dutt\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|Film producer}}\n| education          = [[The Lawrence School, Sanawar]]\n| parents            = [[Sunil Dutt]]<br/>[[Nargis Dutt]]\n| relatives          = See [[List of Hindi film clans#Dutt family (of Sunil Dutt)|Dutt family]]\n| years_active       = 1981\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Richa Sharma (actress)|Richa Sharma]]<br />|1987|1996|end=d.}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Rhea Pillai]]<br />|1998|2008|end=div.}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-would-love-to-write-my-biography-Sanjay-Dutt/articleshow/11860665.cms |title= I would love to write my biography: Sanjay Dutt |publisher= [[The Times of India]] |date= 13 February 2012 |accessdate= 3 October 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151215054943/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-would-love-to-write-my-biography-Sanjay-Dutt/articleshow/11860665.cms |archive-date= 15 December 2015 |url-status=live |df= dmy-all }}</ref><br/>{{marriage|[[Manyata Dutt]]<br />|2008}}\n| children           = 3\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Sanjay Dutt|Full list]]\n}}\n\n'''Sanjay Balraj Dutt'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sanjay-dutt |title=Sanjay Dutt |access-date=28 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028231147/https://www.indiatoday.in/sanjay-dutt |archive-date=28 October 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/mad-genius/sanjay-dutt-1260802|title=Sanjay Dutt|date=2016-07-29|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref> is an Indian actor, author and film producer who works in [[Bollywood|Hindi films]]. He is the recipient of [[List of awards and nominations received by Sanjay Dutt|several awards]], including two [[Filmfare Awards]] and three [[Screen Awards]]. Dutt has appeared in 187 films, ranging from romance to comedy genres, but is usually [[Typecasting (acting)|typecasted]] in action genres.\n\nThe son of actors [[Sunil Dutt]] and [[Nargis]], Dutt made his acting debut in ''[[Rocky (1981 film)|Rocky]]'' (1981), which was directed by his father. The crime thriller ''[[Naam (1986 film)|Naam]]'' (1985) proved to be a turning point in his career, which was followed by a series of commercially successful films in that decade, including ''[[Jeete Hain Shaan Se]]'' (1988), ''[[Mardon Wali Baat]]'' (1988), ''[[Ilaaka]]'' (1989), ''[[Hum Bhi Insaan Hain (1989 film)|Hum Bhi Insaan Hain]]'' (1989) and ''[[Kanoon Apna Apna]]'' (1989). He earned nominations for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor]] for ''[[Saajan]]'' (1991) and ''[[Khalnayak]]'' (1993). Dutt earned his first Best Actor at the ceremony for playing a common man-turned-gangster in ''[[Vaastav: The Reality]]'' (1999). Along with ''Vaastav: The Reality'', he also won accolades for playing an army officer in ''[[Mission Kashmir]]'' (2001), a soft-hearted goofy gangster in ''[[Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.]]'' (2003) and its sequel ''[[Lage Raho Munna Bhai]]'' (2006).\n\nDutt was arrested under the [[Terrorist and Disruptive Activities (Prevention) Act|TADA]] and the [[Arms Act, 1959|Arms Act]] in April 1993 and was convicted for violation of Arms Act for possession of illegal weapons procured from other accused in the [[1993 Bombay bombings]]. After serving his sentence, he was released in 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/from-arrest-to-release-a-complete-23-year-long-sanjay-dutt-timeline/story-7lEBOzaghF8UDsUiwBLKyO.html | title= From arrest to release: A complete, 23-year-long Sanjay Dutt timeline| publisher=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=25 February  2016 | accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2013/03/21/world/asia/india-actor-sentenced/index.html | title=Bollywood star Sanjay Dutt ordered to prison for gun possession| publisher=[[CNN]]|date=22 March  2013 | accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-21873316 | title= Sanjay Dutt: Bollywood actor sent back to jail for 1993 Mumbai blasts| publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=21 March 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Dutt's life receives considerable media coverage in India, and in 2018, ''[[Sanju]]'', a biopic based on his life (which also saw a special appearance by him), was released to positive reviews and emerged as one of the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossers of Indian cinema]].\n\n== Early life ==\nSanjay Balraj Dutt was born in a [[Punjabis|Punjabi]] family at [[Mumbai]]. His parents were noted cinema actors [[Sunil Dutt]] (born Balraj Dutt) and [[Nargis]] (born Fatima Rashid). He has two sisters, [[Priya Dutt]] and Namrata Dutt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/No-sister-gets-along-with-her-brothers-wife-Dutt/articleshow/3997120.cms|title=No sister gets along with her brother's wife: Dutt|access-date=30 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924215354/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/No-sister-gets-along-with-her-brothers-wife-Dutt/articleshow/3997120.cms|archive-date=24 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/namrata-dutt-sanju-sanjay-dutt-5256351/|title=Namrata Dutt reacts after watching Sanju: I didn't connect with Paresh Rawal and Manisha Koirala|access-date=12 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712184632/https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/namrata-dutt-sanju-sanjay-dutt-5256351/|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His mother died in 1981, shortly before his debut film's premiere; her death is cited as the instigator of his drug abuse.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Dutt used to Drugs|url=http://www.bollywoodmantra.com/news/sanjay-dutt-drug-addiction-jail-stints-and-failed-marriages/2214/|publisher=bollywoodmantra.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927231829/http://www.bollywoodmantra.com/news/sanjay-dutt-drug-addiction-jail-stints-and-failed-marriages/2214/|archive-date=27 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> As a child actor, Dutt appeared briefly as a [[qawali]] singer in the 1972 film ''[[Reshma Aur Shera]]'', which starred his father.<ref>{{cite web|author1=PTI|title=Sanjay Dutt to do a qawwali after 41 years in Zanjeer|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/sanjay-dutt-to-do-a-qawwali-after-41-years-in-zanjeer/|website=The Indian Express|accessdate=2016-05-17|date=2 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807055352/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/sanjay-dutt-to-do-a-qawwali-after-41-years-in-zanjeer/|archive-date=7 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{See also|Sanjay Dutt filmography|List of awards and nominations received by Sanjay Dutt}}\n\n=== 1981\u20131997 ===\nDutt made his [[Bollywood]] movie debut with the box-office super hit ''[[Rocky (1981 film)|Rocky]]'' in 1981. Dutt then went on to star in ''[[Vidhaata]]'', the highest-grossing Hindi film of 1982,  along with film veterans [[Dilip Kumar]], [[Shammi Kapoor]] and [[Sanjeev Kumar]]. He also starred in movies like ''[[Main Awara Hoon]]'' (1983). In 1985 he shot ''[[Jaan Ki Baazi]]'', his first film in two years.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/sanjay-dutt-on-the-wrong-side-of-the-law/|title=Sanjay Dutt \u2013 On the wrong side of the law|date=16 May 2013|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064811/https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-others/sanjay-dutt-on-the-wrong-side-of-the-law/|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe 1986 film ''[[Naam (1986 film)|Naam]]'' was a turning point in Dutt's career, it was a major commercial and critical success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/44956266.cms|title=Naam: The film Kumar Gaurav made for buddy Sanjay Dutt - Times of India|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181130114445/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/44956266.cms|archive-date=30 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"thehindu.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/2000/12/08/stories/09080221.htm|title=The Hindu : Like a phoenix he rises again|newspaper=The Hindu|date=8 December 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/> Dutt appeared in successful films throughout the '80s such as ''Imaandaar'', ''[[Inaam Dus Hazaar]]'', ''[[Jeete Hain Shaan Se]]'' (1988), ''[[Mardon Wali Baat]]'' (1988), ''[[Ilaaka]]'' (1989), ''[[Hum Bhi Insaan Hain (1989 film)|Hum Bhi Insaan Hain]]'' (1989), ''[[Kanoon Apna Apna]]'' (1989) and ''[[Taaqatwar]].''<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/>\n\nHis performances in both ''[[Kabzaa]]'' (1988) and [[J. P. Dutta]]'s 1989 ''[[Hathyar (1989 film)|Hathyar]]'' were both well received by critics although both films only managed average collections at the box office.<ref name=\"stargold.in\">{{cite web|title=Sanjay received critical acclaim for Kabzaa|url=http://www.stargold.in/newsdetails.aspx?nid=4451|publisher=stargold.in|accessdate=2013-08-22}}</ref><ref name=\"stargold.in\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay received critical acclaim for Kabzaa And Hathyar|url=http://movies.addatoday.com/2012/05/about-sanjay-dutt-biography.html|publisher=movies.addatoday.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113015447/http://movies.addatoday.com/2012/05/about-sanjay-dutt-biography.html|archive-date=13 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay rece|url=http://movies.addatoday.com/2012/05/about-sanjay-dutt-biography.html|publisher=movies.addatoday.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113015447/http://movies.addatoday.com/2012/05/about-sanjay-dutt-biography.html|archive-date=13 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the late 1980s he was seen in a number of multi-starrers alongside actors like [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]], [[Mithun Chakraborty|Mithun]], [[Dharmendra]], [[Jackie Shroff]] and [[Sunny Deol]].<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/>\n\nHis successes continued in the 1990s, with films that include ''[[Tejaa]]'', ''[[Khatarnaak]]'', ''[[Zahreelay]]'', ''[[Thanedaar]]'', ''[[Khoon Ka Karz]]'', ''[[Yalgaar (India film)|Yalgaar]]'', ''[[Gumrah (1993 film)|Gumrah]]'', ''[[Sahibaan]]'' and ''[[Aatish: Feel the Fire]]''. He went on to star in some of the most era-defining Indian films of the early 1990s such as ''[[Sadak]]'', ''[[Saajan]]'' (for which he was nominated for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Filmfare Best Actor Award]]) and ''[[Khalnayak]]'', for which he earned his second Filmfare Best Actor Award nomination.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/>\n\n''[[The Hindu]]'' wrote that ''\"Sanjay's earlier films (like Naam and Sadak) got him a lot of favourable attention.\"'' and \"Saajan'' established Sanjay Dutt as the conventional soft hero.\"''<ref name=\"thehindu.com\"/>''[[Saajan]]'' was the highest-grossing [[Bollywood films of 1991#Highest grossing|Bollywood film of 1991]], and [[Sadak]] was the sixth highest grosser of 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=197&catName=MTk5MQ==|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115230117/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=197&catName=MTk5MQ==|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 January 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com|date=15 January 2013|publisher=}}</ref> ''[[Khalnayak]]'' was a box office success. The movie was the second-highest grosser of 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=199&catName=MTk5Mw==|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017072516/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=199&catName=MTk5Mw==|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 October 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com|date=17 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref> This was followed by another box office success [[Gumrah (1993 film)|''Gumrah'']], this was Dutt's second consecutive hit of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1054253/10-movies-we-couldnt-imagine-without-sanju-baba/|title=10 movies we couldn't imagine without Sanju Baba - The Express Tribune|date=21 March 2016|publisher=|access-date=9 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809121848/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1054253/10-movies-we-couldnt-imagine-without-sanju-baba/|archive-date=9 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 1997\u2013present ===\n\nDutt's first film after his 1993 arrest was ''[[Daud (film)|Daud]]'' (1997). It did not do well at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficeindia.com/years.php?year=1997&pageId=4|title=Top India Total Nett Gross 1997 - - Box Office India|website=www.boxofficeindia.com|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064750/https://www.boxofficeindia.com/years.php?year=1997&pageId=4|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He followed this with the 1998 ''[[Dushman (1998 film)|Dushman]]'' which did well at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficeindia.com/years.php?year=1998&pageId=4|title=Top India Total Nett Gross 1998 - - Box Office India|website=www.boxofficeindia.com|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064813/https://www.boxofficeindia.com/years.php?year=1998&pageId=4|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> 1999 was an excellent year for Dutt and one that is regarded as his comeback, with all of his five releases being amongst the highest-grossing films of that year. He began it by starring in the Mahesh Bhatt-directed hit ''[[Kartoos]]'', followed by ''[[Khoobsurat (1999 film)|Khoobsurat]]'', ''[[Haseena Maan Jaayegi]]'', ''[[Daag (1999 film)|Daag: The Fire]]'' and ''[[Vaastav: The Reality]]'', for which he won many awards, including his first Filmfare Best Actor Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/entertainment/bollywood/sanjay-dutt-turns-57/ss-BBpUr2p|title=Sanjay Dutt turns 57|website=www.msn.com|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709035301/https://www.msn.com/en-in/entertainment/bollywood/sanjay-dutt-turns-57/ss-BBpUr2p|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/sanjay-dutt-feels-his-cult-film-vaastav-wasn-t-good-did-you-notice-this-fact-in-sanju/250526|title=Sanjay Dutt feels his cult film Vaastav wasn't good - did you notice this fact in Sanju?|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064616/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/sanjay-dutt-feels-his-cult-film-vaastav-wasn-t-good-did-you-notice-this-fact-in-sanju/250526|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His role in 2000's ''[[Mission Kashmir]]'' won him critical acclaim and a number of awards and nominations.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/> Dutt was also invited by the President of India to [[Rashtrapati Bhavan]] for his performance in the movie.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yFAvxLLVPygC&pg=PA461&lpg=PA461&dq=just+couldn\u2019t+believe+what+was+happening+around+me.+I+was+in+a+haze.+I+was+in+a+state+of+delirium.+I+couldn\u2019t+for+the+life+of+me+believe+that+I+who+was+considered+and+is+still+considered+a+criminal#v=onepage&q=just%20couldn\u2019t%20believe%20what%20was%20happening%20around%20me.%20I%20was%20in%20a%20haze.%20I%20was%20in%20a%20state%20of%20delirium.%20I%20couldn\u2019t%20for%20the%20life%20of%20me%20believe%20that%20I%20who%20was%20considered%20and%20is%20still%20considered%20a%20criminal&f=false|title=Maximum city: Bombay lost and found|isbn=9780144001590|last1=Mehta|first1=Suketu|year=2006}}</ref>\n\nAs the decade went on, he continued to play lead roles in popular and critical successes such as ''[[Jodi No.1]]'' (2001), ''[[Pitaah]]'' (2002), ''[[Kaante]]'' (2002) and the National Award-winning film ''[[Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.]]'' (2003), which garnered him several awards.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/> At the box office ''Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.'' achieved a silver jubilee status (25-week run) being one of only eight films to have achieved this status since the year 2000. In its 26th week of release, the film could still be found playing on 257 screens throughout India.<ref name=g>{{cite web|author=|title=Top Earners 2003|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=209&catName=MjAwMw==|publisher=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=10 July 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120525225820/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=209&catName=MjAwMw==|archivedate=25 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsx.com/programmes/at-the-movies-with-anupama-chopra/at-the-movies-with-anupama-chopra-in-conversation-with-rajkumar-hirani-on-his-first-directorial-venture-munna-bhai-mbbs |title=Archived copy |access-date=19 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919094610/https://www.newsx.com/programmes/at-the-movies-with-anupama-chopra/at-the-movies-with-anupama-chopra-in-conversation-with-rajkumar-hirani-on-his-first-directorial-venture-munna-bhai-mbbs |archive-date=19 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Later successes came with ''[[Musafir (2004 film)|Musafir]]'' (2004), ''[[Plan]]'' (2004), ''[[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]]'' (2005) and ''[[Dus]]'' (2005). He won critical acclaim for his performances in ''[[Shabd (film)|Shabd]]'' (2005) and ''[[Zinda (film)|Zinda]]''.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com1\"/>\n\nThe sequel of ''Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.'', ''[[Lage Raho Munna Bhai]]'' was released in late 2006. Dutt received a number of awards for his performance in the film, along with an award from the Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] for his work in the ''Munna bhai'' series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Received award by PM|url=http://www.in.com/sanjay-dutt/biography-284.html|publisher=www.in.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113100610/http://www.in.com/sanjay-dutt/biography-284.html|archive-date=13 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[NDTV India]] counted the character ''[[Munna Bhai]]'' as one of top 20 fictional characters in Bollywood.<ref>[http://movies.ndtv.com/photos/indian-cinema-100-bollywood-s-20-best-characters-15056/slide/3 Indian cinema@100: Bollywood's 20 best characters - NDTV] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620101214/http://movies.ndtv.com/photos/indian-cinema-100-bollywood-s-20-best-characters-15056/slide/3 |date=20 June 2018 }}. [[NDTV]]. Retrieved 14 July 2014</ref> Later Dutt starred in movies like ''[[Dhamaal]]'' (2007), ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]'' (2007), ''[[All the Best: Fun Begins|All the Best]]'' (2009), ''[[Double Dhamaal]]'' (2011), ''[[Son of Sardaar]]'' (2012) ''[[Agneepath (2012 film)|Agneepath]]'' (2012) and ''[[PK (film)|PK]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.spotboye.com/bollywood/listed/looking-back-at-sanjay-dutt-s-journey/567c060817b6144b64adb15c |title=Looking Back at Sanjay Dutt's Journey |access-date=3 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903215124/https://www.spotboye.com/bollywood/listed/looking-back-at-sanjay-dutt-s-journey/567c060817b6144b64adb15c |archive-date=3 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, the Indian film Institute Filmfare listed 12 films featuring Dutt in its list of top 100 highest-grossing movies of all time. In its May 2013 edition \"100 years of Indian cinema\" Filmfare listed three films featuring Dutt in its top 20 list of highest-grossing Hindi films of all time, adjusted for inflation these films were ''Lage Raho Munna Bhai'', ''Khalnayak'' and ''Saajan''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/299794|title=#4 Key Turning Points in the Career of Bollywood's favourite Baba|first=Nidhi|last=Singh|date=7 September 2017|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064755/https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/299794|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVidhu Vinod Chopra on 29 September 2016 announced that the third part of Munna Bhai series, starring Dutt in the title role, would begin soon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/work-on-munnabhai-3-to-begin-next-year-vidhu-vinod-chopra/1/776723.html|title=Work on Munnabhai 3 to begin next year: Vidhu Vinod Chopra|website=India Today|access-date=9 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009202407/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/work-on-munnabhai-3-to-begin-next-year-vidhu-vinod-chopra/1/776723.html|archive-date=9 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, Dutt appeared as the lead in ''[[Bhoomi (film)|Bhoomi]]'', directed by [[Omung Kumar]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Omung-Kumar%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%98Bhoomi%E2%80%99-to-be-Sanjay-Dutt%E2%80%99s-comeback-film/article16668989.ece|title=Omung Kumar's 'Bhoomi' to be Sanjay Dutt's comeback film|date=20 November 2016|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|access-date=10 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214111603/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Omung-Kumar%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%98Bhoomi%E2%80%99-to-be-Sanjay-Dutt%E2%80%99s-comeback-film/article16668989.ece|archive-date=14 December 2016|url-status=live|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> In 2018, he starred in ''Saheb, Biwi Aur Gangster 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/movies-to-look-forward-to/sd/photostory/58803816.cms|title=Pic: Sanjay Dutt's new look for 'Saheb Biwi Aur Gangster 3' is menacing - Movies to look forward to {{!}} The Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909151308/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/movies-to-look-forward-to/sd/photostory/58803816.cms|archive-date=9 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/saheb-biwi-aur-gangster-3-sanjay-dutt-chitrangada-singh-begin-shooting-in-rajasthan/story-u91f4APbiAYtFzwYOaKjeK.html|title=Saheb Biwi Aur Gangster 3: Sanjay Dutt, Chitrangada Singh begin shooting in Rajasthan|date=2017-09-28|work=hindustantimes.com|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928151639/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/saheb-biwi-aur-gangster-3-sanjay-dutt-chitrangada-singh-begin-shooting-in-rajasthan/story-u91f4APbiAYtFzwYOaKjeK.html|archive-date=28 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, it was also announced that Dutt would feature alongside [[Ranbir Kapoor]] and [[Vaani Kapoor]] in ''Shamshera,'' which will release on 31 July 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yashrajfilms.com/movies/shamshera|title=Shamshera|website=www.yashrajfilms.com|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> On 29 June 2018, his biopic ''[[Sanju]]'' released in which he made a special appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/bollywood/sanjay-dutt-stars-in-sanju|title=Confirmed! Sanjay Dutt Makes an Appearance in 'Sanju'|publisher=|date=28 June 2018}}</ref> Dutt and [[Alia Bhatt]] are currently shooting for ''[[Sadak#Sequel|Sadak 2]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/confirmed-alia-bhatt-sanjay-dutt-star-mahesh-bhatts-sadak-2-exclusive-details-full-star-cast/ |title=CONFIRMED! Alia Bhatt \u2013 Sanjay Dutt to star in Mahesh Bhatt's Sadak 2 (EXCLUSIVE details on full star cast) |date=1 September 2018 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |access-date=6 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904172648/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/confirmed-alia-bhatt-sanjay-dutt-star-mahesh-bhatts-sadak-2-exclusive-details-full-star-cast/ |archive-date=4 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In 2019, he joined the cast of historical film ''Bhuj: The Pride of India'', which will feature an ensemble cast consisting of [[Ajay Devgn]], [[Sonakshi Sinha]] and [[Parineeti Chopra]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/bhuj-the-pride-of-india-sanjay-dutt-sonakshi-sinha-rana-daggubati-parineeti-chopra-and-ammy-virk-join-the-ajay-devgn-starrer/articleshow/68493083.cms|title='Bhuj: The Pride of India': Sanjay Dutt, Sonakshi Sinha, Rana Daggubati, Parineeti Chopra and Ammy Virk join the Ajay Devgn starrer - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> He will soon be seen in the film [[Prassthanam]] on 20 September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/prasthanam-teaser-sanjay-dutt-takes-no-prisoners-as-politician-in-war-of-legacy-2077177 |title = Prasthanam Teaser: Sanjay Dutt Takes No Prisoners as Politician in War of Legacy}}</ref>\n\n== Off-screen work ==\nDutt co-hosted the [[Bigg Boss 5|fifth season]] of the Indian reality show ''[[Bigg Boss]]'' along with [[Salman Khan]]. The show aired on ''Colors'' television from 2 October 2011 to 7 January 2012.<ref name=\"Sanjay Dutt, Salman to host Bigg Boss 5 together\">{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt, Salman to host Bigg Boss 5 together|url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2011/jul/200711-informer-2.htm|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=Mi Day|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123215525/http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2011/jul/200711-informer-2.htm|archive-date=23 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Dutt later said it was Khan who persuaded him to co-host the show.<ref name=\"Salman convinced me for Bigg Boss: Sanjay Dutt\">{{cite news|title=Salman convinced me for Bigg Boss: Sanjay Dutt|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Television/Salman-convinced-me-for-Bigg-Boss-Sanjay-Dutt/Article1-752439.aspx|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=Hindustan Times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106030402/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Television/salman-convinced-me-for-bigg-boss-sanjay-dutt/Article1-752439.aspx|archivedate=6 January 2012}}</ref> Dutt and entrepreneur [[Indian Premier League]] cricket team owner [[Raj Kundra]] together launched India's first professionally organised [[mixed martial arts]] league\u2014the [[Super Fight League]]\u2014on 16 January 2012.<ref name=TOI01172012>{{cite news |title=Ready for the Super Fight League? |newspaper=The Times Of India |location=Mumbai |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-17/news-interviews/30632385_1_mma-sport-fight-night |first=Roshni |last=Olivera |accessdate=2012-01-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212031726/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-17/news-interviews/30632385_1_mma-sport-fight-night |archive-date=12 December 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and media image ==\n[[File:SanjayDutt-ManyataDutt.jpg|thumb|240px|right|Dutt with wife Manyata in 2011]]\nIn the early 1980s, Dutt had a relationship with his co-star from his first film, [[Tina Ambani|Tina Munim]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodshaadis.com/articles/throwback-interview-of-sanjay-dutt-about-ex-girlfriend-tina-munim-9258|title=Throwback Interview Of Sanjay Dutt About Ex-Girlfriend Tina Munim: I Am Very Possessive About Her|website=BollywoodShaadis|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> After this relationship ended, Dutt married actress [[Richa Sharma (actress)|Richa Sharma]] in 1987.<ref name=\"trib1\">{{cite web|title=I have become a family man: Sanjay Dutt|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/61609/i-have-become-a-family-man-sanjay-dutt/|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=2010-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111133252/http://tribune.com.pk/story/61609/i-have-become-a-family-man-sanjay-dutt/|archive-date=11 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> She died of a brain tumour in 1996. The couple have a daughter, Trishala, born in 1988, who lives in the United States with her maternal grandparents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/dutt/20080704.htm|title=Sanjay Dutt's tearful reunion with daughter|publisher=|access-date=10 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710041308/http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/dutt/20080704.htm|archive-date=10 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Dutt's second marriage was to air-hostess-turned-model [[Rhea Pillai]] in February 1998.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sanjay Weds |url=http://www.screenindia.com/feb27/news.htm |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010825183940/http://www.screenindia.com/feb27/news.htm |archivedate=25 August 2001}}</ref> The divorce finalised in 2008. Dutt married [[Manyata Dutt|Manyata]] (born Dilnawaz Sheikh)<ref>{{cite web|title=Unknown starlet Dilnawaz's journey to Mrs Manyata Dutt|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/unknown-starlet-dilnawazs-journey-to-mrs-manyata-dutt/83359-8.html|publisher=Ibnlive.in|accessdate=2010-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808150620/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/unknown-starlet-dilnawazs-journey-to-mrs-manyata-dutt/83359-8.html|archive-date=8 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> first registered in [[Goa]] in 2008 and then, in a [[Hindu]] ceremony in [[Mumbai]], after two years of dating.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sanjay Dutt marries Manyata |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-31876920080211 |work=Reuters |accessdate=2010-10-21 |date=11 February 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418014230/http://in.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-31876920080211 |archive-date=18 April 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref> On 21 October 2010, he became a father to twins, a boy and a girl.<ref>{{cite news|title=Manyata Dutt delivers twins |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-21/news-interviews/28247462_1_manyata-dutt-twins-trishala|work=Times of India|accessdate=2010-10-21 |date=21 October 2010}}</ref> He is a devout [[Shaivism|Shaiva]] [[Hindu]] who has read holy scriptures and theological works.<ref>[http://www.deccanchronicle.com/amp/entertainment/bollywood/210316/sanjay-dutt-to-work-for-jail-reforms-1.html/ Personal Life Material] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024044245/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/amp/entertainment/bollywood/210316/sanjay-dutt-to-work-for-jail-reforms-1.html/ |date=24 October 2017 }} - Religious Views Source</ref>\n\nBombay (now Mumbai) suffered a series of [[1993 Bombay bombings|serial bombings in 1993]]. Dutt was among several people associated with Bollywood who were accused of involvement. It was alleged that Dutt accepted a delivery of weapons at his house from [[Abu Salem]] and co-accused Riyaz Siddiqui, who had also been implicated in relation to the Mumbai blasts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=174294 |title=Charges framed against Salem|publisher=Indian Express|accessdate=2009-04-19|date=18 March 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829173254/http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=174294 |archivedate=29 August 2009}}</ref> It was claimed that the weapons formed a part of a large consignment of arms connected to the terrorists.<ref name=\"ibn\" /> Dutt, however, in his confession stated that he took only one [[Type 56 assault rifle|Type-56]] from the producers of his movie ''Sanam'', for his own family protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/1993-mumbai-blasts-sanjay-dutts-confessional-statement-598327.html|title=1993 Mumbai blasts: Sanjay Dutt's confessional statement|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064626/https://www.news18.com/news/india/1993-mumbai-blasts-sanjay-dutts-confessional-statement-598327.html|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It has also been reported that Sanjay Dutt's father [[Sunil Dutt]]'s political rivalry caused Sanjay Dutt's conviction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/reel-vs-real-the-politics-behind-the-life-and-crimes-of-sanjay-dutt-118070900115_1.html|title=Reel vs real: The politics behind the life and crimes of Sanjay Dutt|first=Rasheed|last=Kidwai|date=9 July 2018|publisher=|via=Business Standard|access-date=24 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724154341/https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/reel-vs-real-the-politics-behind-the-life-and-crimes-of-sanjay-dutt-118070900115_1.html|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1993, he was arrested under the provisions of the [[Terrorist and Disruptive Activities (Prevention) Act]] (TADA).<ref name=\"ibn\">{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sanjay-dutt-gets-6-yrs-jail-taken-into-custody/45923-4-single.html|title=Sanjay Dutt gets 6 yrs jail, taken into custody |publisher=IBN |accessdate=2009-04-19 |date=31 July 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091219154300/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sanjay-dutt-gets-6-yrs-jail-taken-into-custody/45923-4-single.html|archivedate=19 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Ryan Clarke |title=Crime-Terror Nexus in South Asia: States, Security and Non-State Actors |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQcbIfg739IC&pg=PA58|accessdate=2013-05-16|date=12 April 2011 |publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-136-73970-5|pages=58\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sanjay-dutt-gets-fiveyear-jail-term-in-1993-mumbai-blasts/1091259/ |title=Sanjay Dutt sentenced to 5 years in jail, gets 4 weeks to surrender |publisher=Indian Express |date=2013-03-22 |accessdate=2013-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323192432/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sanjay-dutt-gets-fiveyear-jail-term-in-1993-mumbai-blasts/1091259 |archive-date=23 March 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Dutt was granted bail by the [[Supreme Court of India]] on 5 May 1993; however, on 4 July 1994 his bail was cancelled and he was re-arrested. On 16 October 1995 he was granted bail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/from-arrest-to-release-a-complete-23-year-long-sanjay-dutt-timeline/story-7lEBOzaghF8UDsUiwBLKyO.html|title=From arrest to release: A complete, 23-year-long Sanjay Dutt timeline|date=25 February 2016|publisher=|access-date=9 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709064548/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/from-arrest-to-release-a-complete-23-year-long-sanjay-dutt-timeline/story-7lEBOzaghF8UDsUiwBLKyO.html|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Abdul Qayyum Abdul Karim Shaikh, who was thought to be a close aide of the terrorists' ringleader, [[Dawood Ibrahim]], was arrested.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/man-who-supplied-pistol-to-sanjay-dutt-arrested/23273/|title=Man who supplied pistol to Sanjay Dutt arrested|publisher=Indian Express|accessdate=2009-04-19|date=14 February 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829195011/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/man-who-supplied-pistol-to-sanjay-dutt-arrested/23273/|archive-date=29 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Dutt had given Qayuum's name to the police when confessing to arms possession, saying that in September 1992 he had bought a [[pistol]] from Qayuum in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/feb/13shaikh.htm|title=93 blast accused Abdul Qayyum Shaikh arrested|publisher=[[rediff.com]]|accessdate=2009-04-19|date=13 February 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090830104020/http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/feb/13shaikh.htm|archive-date=30 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2007, Dutt was cleared of the charges relating to the Mumbai blast; however, the TADA court sentenced Dutt to six years' [[rigorous imprisonment]] under Arms act for illegal possession of weapons.<ref name=\"ibn\" /><ref name=star>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/aug/01/film.india|title=Bollywood star gets six years as lengthy Mumbai bombing trial ends|author=Randeep Ramesh|newspaper=the Guardian|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231081329/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/aug/01/film.india|archive-date=31 December 2016|url-status=live|date=August 2007}}</ref> According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', \"The actor claimed he feared for his life after the notorious 'Black Friday' bombings, which were allegedly staged by Mumbai's Muslim-dominated mafia in retaliation for deadly Hindu-Muslim clashes a few months earlier. But the judge rejected this defence and also refused bail.\"<ref name=star/> Dutt was returned to jail at Arthur Road and soon after moved to the [[Yerawada Central Jail]] in [[Pune]].<ref name=\"ibn\"/><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/story.aspx?id=NEWEN20070021271 | title = Priya to approach SC for Sanju's bail | author = Imtiaz Jaleel | publisher = NDTV | date = 2 August 2007 | accessdate = 31 July 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225512/http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/story.aspx?id=NEWEN20070021271 | archivedate = 26 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Dutt appealed against the sentence<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6934560.stm|title=BBC NEWS - South Asia - Bollywood's Dutt appeals sentence|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121152918/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6934560.stm|archive-date=21 January 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> and was granted interim bail on 20 August 2007 until such time as the TADA court provided him with a copy of its judgement.<ref>[http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2007/08/20/9955/index.html Sanjay Dutt gets bail. He was biif] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829180603/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2007/08/20/9955/index.html |date=29 August 2009 }}</ref> On 22 October 2007 Dutt was back in jail but again applied for bail. On 27 November 2007, Dutt was granted bail by the Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2580913.cms|title=Sanjay Dutt released from Pune jail|work=The Times of India|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829225338/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2580913.cms|archive-date=29 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March 2013 the Supreme Court upheld the verdict but shortened the sentence to five years' imprisonment. Dutt was given a month to surrender before the authorities.<ref name=\"As it happened: I\u2019ve been a good human, says Dutt\">{{cite news|title=As it happened: I've been a good human, says Sanjay Dutt|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/as-it-happened-ive-been-a-good-human-says-sanjay-dutt-669614.html|accessdate=2013-05-17|newspaper=First Post|date=21 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526025204/http://www.firstpost.com/india/as-it-happened-ive-been-a-good-human-says-sanjay-dutt-669614.html|archive-date=26 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDutt has said that \"I am not a politician but I belong to a political family.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/topNews/idINIndia-37493320090116?sp=true |title=Sanjay Dutt to contest elections on Samajwadi Party ticket |publisher=Reuters |date=16 January 2009 |access-date=16 January 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904201406/http://in.reuters.com/article/topNews/idINIndia-37493320090116?sp=true |archive-date=4 September 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was persuaded by a close friend to contest the [[2009 Indian general election|2009 Lok Sabha elections]] as a candidate for the [[Samajwadi Party]], but withdrew when the court refused to suspend his conviction.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sanjay-dutt-cant-contest-polls-supreme-court/89121-37.html |title=Sanjay Dutt can't contest polls: Supreme Court |publisher=IBN |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016032036/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sanjay-dutt-cant-contest-polls-supreme-court/89121-37.html |archivedate=16 October 2012 |date=31 March 2009}}</ref> He was then appointed General Secretary of the Samajwadi Party, leaving that post in December 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Dutt leaves the post of Samajwadi Party|url=http://in.news.yahoo.com/sanjay-dutt-s-20-year-nightmare-094611351.html|publisher=yahoo|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005021131/http://in.news.yahoo.com/sanjay-dutt-s-20-year-nightmare-094611351.html|archive-date=5 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2013 the Supreme Court upheld Dutt's five-year sentence, 18 months of which he already spent in jail during the trial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/sanjay-dutt-convicted-in-1993-bombay-blasts-case-gets-5-years-in-jail-345095?pfrom=home-lateststories |title=Sanjay Dutt convicted in 1993 Bombay blasts case, gets 5 years in jail |publisher=NDTV.com |date=2013-03-21 |accessdate=2013-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323234256/http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/sanjay-dutt-convicted-in-1993-bombay-blasts-case-gets-5-years-in-jail-345095?pfrom=home-lateststories |archive-date=23 March 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was given four weeks to surrender to the authorities, the court having refused to release him on probation due to the severity of the offence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Dutt given 4 Weeks to surrender|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/sc-grants-4-weeks-more-to-Sanjay-Dutt-to-surrender/article4627135.ece|publisher=hindubusinessline.com|accessdate=2013-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230233441/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/sc-grants-4-weeks-more-to-sanjay-dutt-to-surrender/article4627135.ece|archive-date=30 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May, the Supreme Court rejected Dutt's [[review petition]] for the reconsideration of his conviction and asked him to surrender on the stipulated date.<ref>{{cite news|title=1993 Mumbai blasts case: 1993 Bombay blast case: Supreme Court dismisses Sanjay Dutt's review petition|newspaper=Economic Times|location=Mumbai|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/1993-bombay-blast-case-supreme-court-dismisses-sanjay-dutts-review-petition/articleshow/19986334.cms|access-date=10 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921124911/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/1993-bombay-blast-case-supreme-court-dismisses-sanjay-dutts-review-petition/articleshow/19986334.cms|archive-date=21 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Review plea rejected: Sanjay Dutt will have to go to Jail|url=http://southmonitor.com/2013/05/11/review-plea-rejected-sanjay-dutt-will-have-to-go-to-jail/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909031023/http://southmonitor.com/2013/05/11/review-plea-rejected-sanjay-dutt-will-have-to-go-to-jail/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-09-09|publisher=Southmonitor.com}}</ref> on 14 May, Dutt withdrew the mercy plea and surrendered to the Mumbai Police on 16 May 2013.<ref name=\"Sanjay Dutt withdraws plea, set to surrender before TADA court tomorrow\">{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt withdraws plea, set to surrender before TADA court tomorrow/1116049/?rheditorpick#sthash.mToe0p5t.dpuf|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sanjay-dutt-withdraws-plea-set-to-surrender-before-jail-tomorrow/1116049/?rheditorpick|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=Indian Express|date=16 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Sanjay Dutt reaches Tada court, will surrender shortly\">{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt reaches Tada court, will surrender shortly|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-05-16/india/39309264_1_imperial-heights-sanjay-dutt-manyata|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=The Times of India|date=16 May 2013}}</ref> Just before the surrender, the Mumbai jail authority got an anonymous letter threatening Dutt's life. Dutt filed an appeal to allow him to surrender before entering Yerwada Central Jail. Later, Dutt withdrew this request too.<ref name=\"Sanjay Dutt to surrender today, jail gets threat letter\">{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt to surrender today, jail gets threat letter|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-05-16/india/39309404_1_sanjay-dutt-yerwada-jail-letter-threat|accessdate=2013-05-16|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref> He was paroled from 21 December 2013. The parole was extended three times until March 2014, raising concern in Bombay High Court and a proposal from the [[Government of Maharashtra]] to amend the law of parole. He returned to Yerwada Central Jail after his parole ended.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sanjay Dutt's parole over, leaves for Yerwada. In December 2014, he was out on Furlough for 14 days again.|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/sanjay-dutt-leaves-home-yerwada-jail/1/350688.html|newspaper=India Today|date=22 March 2014|accessdate=2014-05-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527221758/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/sanjay-dutt-leaves-home-yerwada-jail/1/350688.html|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Dutt was out on a two weeks' furlough granted by the Yerwada Central Jail authorities on 24 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/out-on-parole-sanjay-dutt-watches-pk-with-family-718105|title=Out on Parole, Sanjay Dutt Watches PK With Family|work=NDTVMovies.com|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226112829/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/out-on-parole-sanjay-dutt-watches-pk-with-family-718105|archive-date=26 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>  He was subsequently incarcerated in Yerwada Central Jail, to complete his jail term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sanjay-dutt-shifted-to-punes-yerawada-jail-522972|title=Sanjay Dutt shifted to Pune's Yerawada Jail|author=Rashmi Rajput|date=22 May 2013|work=NDTV.com|accessdate=2015-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518083512/http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sanjay-dutt-shifted-to-punes-yerawada-jail-522972|archive-date=18 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He was released from there on 25 February 2016 after serving his sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-35647886|title=How Bollywood star Sanjay Dutt spent his time in jail|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720080258/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-35647886|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live|date=25 February 2016|last1=Changoiwala|first1=Puja}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nA biopic film based on the life of Dutt, titled ''[[Sanju]]'', in which [[Ranbir Kapoor]] portrays the title character,<ref>{{cite news |work=Indian Express |title=Shooting for Sanjay Dutt biopic featuring Ranbir Kapoor begins, tweets Rajkummar Hirani |date=14 January 2017 |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/shooting-for-sanjay-dutt-biopic-begins-4473777/ |accessdate=2017-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115141557/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/shooting-for-sanjay-dutt-biopic-begins-4473777/ |archive-date=15 January 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> was released on 29 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/sanju-trailer-watch-drama-drugs-and-ranbir-kapoor/article24034889.ece|title='Sanju' trailer watch: drama, drugs and Ranbir Kapoor|last=Desk|first=The Hindu Net|date=2018-05-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-05-30|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/sanju-trailer-heres-how-bollywood-is-applauding-ranbir-kapoor-for-his-performance/articleshow/64383711.cms|title=Sanju Trailer: Here's how Bollywood is applauding Ranbir Kapoor for his performance|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-05-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530175645/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/sanju-trailer-heres-how-bollywood-is-applauding-ranbir-kapoor-for-his-performance/articleshow/64383711.cms|archive-date=30 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box|viaf=64240660}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0004569}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrity/sanjay-dutt/ Sanjay Dutt] at [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n{{Sanjay Dutt}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Sanjay Dutt\n| list =\n{{FilmfareAwardBestActor 1981-2000}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestComedian}}\n{{ScreenAwardBestActor}}\n{{ScreenAwardBestSupportingActor}}\n{{StardustAwardMaleStar}}\n{{ZeeCineAwardBestActorMale}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dutt, Sanjay}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Indian male child actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male singers]]\n[[Category:Lawrence School, Sanawar alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Samajwadi Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian actor-politicians]]\n[[Category:Bigg Boss]]\n[[Category:Indian game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Paroled people]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male comedians]]\n[[Category:Hindi film producers]]\n[[Category:Indian criminals]]\n[[Category:Sanjay Dutt]]\n", "name_user": "Agha.aliSsajjad", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life and media image:Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanjay_Dutt"}
{"title_page": "Ugo Colombo (real estate developer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name           = Ugo Colombo\n|nationality    = Italian\n|known_for      = \n|occupation     = [[Real Estate Developer]], [[Entrepreneur]], [[Philanthropist]]\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Miami]]\n}}'''Ugo Colombo''' ([[Milan]], 2 March 1961) is an Italian-born residential and commercial real estate developer in Miami, Florida.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ugo Colombo|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/UgoCC|publisher=Daily Motion|accessdate=5 June 2014|quote=Ugo Colombo is a Miami residential and commercial real estate developer.}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nColombo was born in [[Milan, Italy]] on March 2, 1961. He was schooled in a [[Lausanne, Switzerland]] boarding school and spent two years working for his father. He came to the US in 1983 and attended the [[University of Miami]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ugocolombo.com/bio/|publisher=Ugo Colombo|accessdate=5 June 2014|title=Biography of Ugo Colombo|quote=Born in 1961 in Milan, Italy, Mr. Colombo came to the United States in 1983.}}</ref><ref name=leg>[http://therealdeal.com/issues_articles/ugo-stakes-his-claim/ Ugo Stakes His Claim ]</ref><ref name=ninee>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924151544/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-20636129.html Life for Miami Real Estate Business Has Not Been All Play]</ref><ref name=style>[http://www.epicmiami.com/flash/pdf/ocean%20drive%2011.2007.pdf Epic Miami Overview]</ref>\n\n==Real estate==\nUgo Colombo's real estate career began when he acquired and resold a group of foreclosed units from the [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]].<ref name=\"Nordheimer\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=NORDHEIMER|first1=JON|title=Nesting Beyond the Snowbirds;Foreigners Flock to Miami's Luxury Condominiums|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/20/business/nesting-beyond-the-snowbirds-foreigners-flock-to-miami-s-luxury-condominiums.html?src=pm&pagewanted=2|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=5 June 2014|date=February 20, 1996|quote=He started snapping up unsold condos auctioned by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation.}}</ref> He then formed his company [[CMC Group]], which focused on the management of distressed real estate in Miami. His company then entered the design and construction industry with a focus on high-rise luxury condominium buildings on Brickell Avenue in Miami, as well as in Aventura and Miami Beach. The first building venture he was a part of was the Villa Regina in Brickell, Miami. One of the next buildings he built was the 1992 Bristol Tower on the same avenue, which cost $80 million. He is also the founder of Glasswall, which creates impact-resistant glass for use in high-rise buildings,<ref name=haute>[http://hauteliving.com/2013/04/haute-100-miami-2/353905/ Haute 100 Miami]</ref><ref name=style /><ref name=Today>[http://cmcgroupmiami.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/2005_Feb_Miami_Today.pdf Miami Today profile]</ref> including hurricane-proof glass.<ref>[http://www.floridatrend.com/print/article/11351 Trendsetters]</ref>\n\nThe Bristol Tower was one of the first buildings added to the Miami skyline in fifteen years when it was developed.<ref name=ninee /> Colombo has stated that he uses glass and metal in his buildings as opposed to concrete for aesthetic reasons.<ref name=style /> One of his buildings, the 54-story [[Santa Maria (building)|Santa Maria]] condominium in Miami, was the tallest American building constructed south of New York City when it was completed in the 1990s.<ref name=Today /> In 2003 Colombo partnered with the developers of a new hotel to replace the [[DuPont Plaza Hotel (Miami)|Dupont Plaza Hotel in Miami]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140714142515/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-98105101.html Miami Developer to Erect Condo Towers on Site of Former Hotel]</ref> Colombo's most recent developments include Epic Residences and Hotel, a 55-story luxury condominium and hotel at the mouth of the Miami River in downtown Miami, and Grovenor House, a 166-unit luxury condominium project completed in 2006 of Miami's [[Coconut Grove]] community.<ref name=\"Tangled\">Smiley, David [http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/22/2863936/developer-tangled-in-beach-convention.html Developer tangled in Miami Beach convention center probe], Miami Herald, retrieved on 21 February 2013</ref>\n\nIn partnership with Portman Holdings, Colombo's CMC Group was one of two groups bidding to redevelop Miami Beach's aging convention center complex.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/blog/morning-edition/2012/12/groups-for-miami-beach-convention.html|title=Miami Beach could shortlist top convention center developers|author=Oscar Pedro Musibay|date=Dec 7, 2012|work=[[South Florida Business Journal]]}}</ref> The project was later investigated due to concerns of bid rigging and Colombo was cleared of any wrongdoing.<ref name=\"Tangled\"/><ref>Smiley, David [http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/08/13/2950334/developer-reportedly-cleared-in.html Developer cleared in Miami Beach convention center bidding probe], Miami Herald,  retrieved on 21 February 2013</ref> At the end of May, 2014 Ugo Colombo established a joint venture with real estate magnate [[Vladislav Doronin]] to develop a number of luxury residential real estate projects in Miami, the first of which is called [[Brickell Flatiron]] with artist Julian Schnabel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Veteran Developers, Ugo Colombo and Vladislav Doronin, Establish Joint Venture to Actively Develop Miami Luxury Residential Real Estate Projects|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/veteran-developers-ugo-colombo-and-vladislav-doronin-establish-joint-venture-to-actively-develop-miami-luxury-residential-real-estate-projects-2014-05-28|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=5 June 2014|date=May 28, 2014|quote=Ugo Colombo's CMC Group Inc. and international real estate developer Vladislav Doronin, chairman and founder of Moscow-based Capital Group, announced they have entered into a joint venture agreement to develop significant new projects in Miami's downtown Brickell area on land they own jointly.}}[https://alamocityhousebuyer.com/]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/15/realestate/using-artists-to-sell-condos-in-miami-and-new-york.html?_r=0 Using Artists to Sell Condos in Miami and New York]</ref> In 2014 Colombo sold an undeveloped parcel of land along the Miami River for $125 million, which he had originally purchased for $25 million in 2006.<ref>https://online.wsj.com/articles/condo-builders-fuel-land-rush-in-miami-1406052941?KEYWORDS=robbie+whelan</ref>\n\n==The Collection==\nIn 1994, Colombo acquired The Collection, a seven-franchise luxury automotive dealership. Colombo bought The Collection after it had been seized by the U.S. government during a drug prosecution case against his ex-racing partner, Armando \"Mandy\" Fernandez.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-5514618_ITM|title=Racing Buddy of Jailed Owner Bids for His Florida Car Dealership|work=Miami Herald|date=May 6, 1994|author=Lyons, David|agency=[[Knight Ridder]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/2005-10-13/news/miami-see-it-like-a-drug-dealer/|title=Miami: See it like a drug dealer|work=Miami New Times|date=October 13, 2005|author=Francisco Alvarado}}</ref><br><br>\nIn 2018, The Collection opened Ferrari of Miami in Downtown Miami's Biscayne Corridor. Upon opening the new stand-alone showroom, The Collection became one of the largest Ferrari dealerships in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reiser |first1=Emon |title=Inside the grand opening of Ferrari of Miami (Photos) |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/news/2018/04/16/inside-the-grand-opening-of-ferrari-of-miami.html |website=South Florida Business Journal}}</ref> In 2018 The Collection also announced plans to open a 400,000 square foot joint Jaguar and Land Rover dealership.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bandell |first1=Brian |title=Coral Gables to consider developments by University of Miami, Jackson Health |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/news/2018/02/20/coral-gables-to-consider-developments-by-um.html |website=South Florida Business Journal}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nUgo Colombo is married to Sara Colombo, who owns the interior design shop NEST in Miami, which specializes in luxury interiors. They have three children together.<ref name=haute /><ref name=style />  The two have also held charitable events in their home, including art auctions in support of Best Buddies International and the Brandt Foundation.<ref>http://hauteliving.com/2013/12/best-buddies-art-friendship-auction-raises-nearly-1-million/425481/#slide-3</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Nordheimer\">{{cite news|last=Nordheimer|first=Jon|title=Nesting Beyond the Snowbirds;Foreigners Flock to Miami's Luxury Condominiums|work=The New York Times|page=1|date=20 February 1996|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/20/business/nesting-beyond-the-snowbirds-foreigners-flock-to-miami-s-luxury-condominiums.html}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colombo, Ugo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Real estate and property developers]]\n[[Category:People from Milan]]\n[[Category:Italian emigrants to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name           = Ugo Colombo\n|nationality    = Italian\n|known_for      = \n|occupation     = [[Real Estate Developer]], [[Entrepreneur]], [[Philanthropist]]\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Miami]]\n}}'''Ugo Colombo''' ([[Milan]], 2 March 1961) is an Italian-born residential and commercial real estate developer in Miami, Florida.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ugo Colombo|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/UgoCC|publisher=Daily Motion|accessdate=5 June 2014|quote=Ugo Colombo is a Miami residential and commercial real estate developer.}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nColombo was born in [[Milan, Italy]] on March 2, 1961. He was schooled in a [[Lausanne, Switzerland]] boarding school and spent two years working for his father's industrial empire. He came to the US in 1983 and attended the [[University of Miami]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ugocolombo.com/bio/|publisher=Ugo Colombo|accessdate=5 June 2014|title=Biography of Ugo Colombo|quote=Born in 1961 in Milan, Italy, Mr. Colombo came to the United States in 1983.}}</ref><ref name=leg>[http://therealdeal.com/issues_articles/ugo-stakes-his-claim/ Ugo Stakes His Claim ]</ref><ref name=ninee>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924151544/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-20636129.html Life for Miami Real Estate Business Has Not Been All Play]</ref><ref name=style>[http://www.epicmiami.com/flash/pdf/ocean%20drive%2011.2007.pdf Epic Miami Overview]</ref>\n\n==Real estate==\nUgo Colombo's real estate career began when he acquired and resold a group of foreclosed units from the [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]].<ref name=\"Nordheimer\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=NORDHEIMER|first1=JON|title=Nesting Beyond the Snowbirds;Foreigners Flock to Miami's Luxury Condominiums|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/20/business/nesting-beyond-the-snowbirds-foreigners-flock-to-miami-s-luxury-condominiums.html?src=pm&pagewanted=2|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=5 June 2014|date=February 20, 1996|quote=He started snapping up unsold condos auctioned by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation.}}</ref> He then formed his company [[CMC Group]], which focused on the management of distressed real estate in Miami. His company then entered the design and construction industry with a focus on high-rise luxury condominium buildings on Brickell Avenue in Miami, as well as in Aventura and Miami Beach. The first building venture he was a part of was the Villa Regina in Brickell, Miami. One of the next buildings he built was the 1992 Bristol Tower on the same avenue, which cost $80 million. He is also the founder of Glasswall, which creates impact-resistant glass for use in high-rise buildings,<ref name=haute>[http://hauteliving.com/2013/04/haute-100-miami-2/353905/ Haute 100 Miami]</ref><ref name=style /><ref name=Today>[http://cmcgroupmiami.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/2005_Feb_Miami_Today.pdf Miami Today profile]</ref> including hurricane-proof glass.<ref>[http://www.floridatrend.com/print/article/11351 Trendsetters]</ref>\n\nThe Bristol Tower was one of the first buildings added to the Miami skyline in fifteen years when it was developed.<ref name=ninee /> Colombo has stated that he uses glass and metal in his buildings as opposed to concrete for aesthetic reasons.<ref name=style /> One of his buildings, the 54-story [[Santa Maria (building)|Santa Maria]] condominium in Miami, was the tallest American building constructed south of New York City when it was completed in the 1990s.<ref name=Today /> In 2003 Colombo partnered with the developers of a new hotel to replace the [[DuPont Plaza Hotel (Miami)|Dupont Plaza Hotel in Miami]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140714142515/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-98105101.html Miami Developer to Erect Condo Towers on Site of Former Hotel]</ref> Colombo's most recent developments include Epic Residences and Hotel, a 55-story luxury condominium and hotel at the mouth of the Miami River in downtown Miami, and Grovenor House, a 166-unit luxury condominium project completed in 2006 of Miami's [[Coconut Grove]] community.<ref name=\"Tangled\">Smiley, David [http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/22/2863936/developer-tangled-in-beach-convention.html Developer tangled in Miami Beach convention center probe], Miami Herald, retrieved on 21 February 2013</ref>\n\nIn partnership with Portman Holdings, Colombo's CMC Group was one of two groups bidding to redevelop Miami Beach's aging convention center complex.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/blog/morning-edition/2012/12/groups-for-miami-beach-convention.html|title=Miami Beach could shortlist top convention center developers|author=Oscar Pedro Musibay|date=Dec 7, 2012|work=[[South Florida Business Journal]]}}</ref> The project was later investigated due to concerns of bid rigging and Colombo was cleared of any wrongdoing.<ref name=\"Tangled\"/><ref>Smiley, David [http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/08/13/2950334/developer-reportedly-cleared-in.html Developer cleared in Miami Beach convention center bidding probe], Miami Herald,  retrieved on 21 February 2013</ref> At the end of May, 2014 Ugo Colombo established a joint venture with real estate magnate [[Vladislav Doronin]] to develop a number of luxury residential real estate projects in Miami, the first of which is called [[Brickell Flatiron]] with artist Julian Schnabel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Veteran Developers, Ugo Colombo and Vladislav Doronin, Establish Joint Venture to Actively Develop Miami Luxury Residential Real Estate Projects|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/veteran-developers-ugo-colombo-and-vladislav-doronin-establish-joint-venture-to-actively-develop-miami-luxury-residential-real-estate-projects-2014-05-28|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=5 June 2014|date=May 28, 2014|quote=Ugo Colombo's CMC Group Inc. and international real estate developer Vladislav Doronin, chairman and founder of Moscow-based Capital Group, announced they have entered into a joint venture agreement to develop significant new projects in Miami's downtown Brickell area on land they own jointly.}}[https://alamocityhousebuyer.com/]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/15/realestate/using-artists-to-sell-condos-in-miami-and-new-york.html?_r=0 Using Artists to Sell Condos in Miami and New York]</ref> In 2014 Colombo sold an undeveloped parcel of land along the Miami River for $125 million, which he had originally purchased for $25 million in 2006.<ref>https://online.wsj.com/articles/condo-builders-fuel-land-rush-in-miami-1406052941?KEYWORDS=robbie+whelan</ref>\n\n==The Collection==\nIn 1994, Colombo acquired The Collection, a seven-franchise luxury automotive dealership. Colombo bought The Collection after it had been seized by the U.S. government during a drug prosecution case against his ex-racing partner, Armando \"Mandy\" Fernandez.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-5514618_ITM|title=Racing Buddy of Jailed Owner Bids for His Florida Car Dealership|work=Miami Herald|date=May 6, 1994|author=Lyons, David|agency=[[Knight Ridder]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/2005-10-13/news/miami-see-it-like-a-drug-dealer/|title=Miami: See it like a drug dealer|work=Miami New Times|date=October 13, 2005|author=Francisco Alvarado}}</ref><br><br>\nIn 2018, The Collection opened Ferrari of Miami in Downtown Miami's Biscayne Corridor. Upon opening the new stand-alone showroom, The Collection became one of the largest Ferrari dealerships in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reiser |first1=Emon |title=Inside the grand opening of Ferrari of Miami (Photos) |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/news/2018/04/16/inside-the-grand-opening-of-ferrari-of-miami.html |website=South Florida Business Journal}}</ref> In 2018 The Collection also announced plans to open a 400,000 square foot joint Jaguar and Land Rover dealership.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bandell |first1=Brian |title=Coral Gables to consider developments by University of Miami, Jackson Health |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/news/2018/02/20/coral-gables-to-consider-developments-by-um.html |website=South Florida Business Journal}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nUgo Colombo is married to Sara Colombo, who owns the interior design shop NEST in Miami, which specializes in luxury interiors. They have three children together.<ref name=haute /><ref name=style />  The two have also held charitable events in their home, including art auctions in support of Best Buddies International and the Brandt Foundation.<ref>http://hauteliving.com/2013/12/best-buddies-art-friendship-auction-raises-nearly-1-million/425481/#slide-3</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Nordheimer\">{{cite news|last=Nordheimer|first=Jon|title=Nesting Beyond the Snowbirds;Foreigners Flock to Miami's Luxury Condominiums|work=The New York Times|page=1|date=20 February 1996|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/20/business/nesting-beyond-the-snowbirds-foreigners-flock-to-miami-s-luxury-condominiums.html}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colombo, Ugo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Real estate and property developers]]\n[[Category:People from Milan]]\n[[Category:Italian emigrants to the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Philcroix91", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Cleaned up self celbr. no source)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ugo_Colombo_(real_estate_developer)"}
{"title_page": "Trick-taking game", "text_new": "{{more sources|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:Four overlapping playing cards.jpg|thumb|<center>'''A trick'''</center><br><small>North led the 10{{Spades}}. Usually all players must ''follow suit'' and play a spade unless they have none. East does so with the K{{spades}}. South doesn't have a spade, he plays the J{{diamonds}}, and West the 7{{hearts}}. In a notrump game, East wins the trick, having played the highest card of the suit led (unless the game is an [[Ace-Ten games|Ace-Ten game]], with 10 being higher than the King, making North win the trick). However, if diamonds or hearts are trumps, South or West respectively win.</small>]]\nA '''trick-taking game''' is a [[card game|card]] or [[tile-based game]] in which play of a ''[[Hand (card games)|hand]]'' centers on a series of finite rounds or units of play, called ''tricks'', which are each evaluated to determine a winner or ''taker'' of that trick. The object of such games then may be closely tied to the number of tricks taken, as in '''plain-trick games''' such as [[Whist]], [[Contract bridge]], [[Spades (card game)|Spades]], [[Napoleon (card game)|Napoleon]], [[Euchre]], Rowboat, Clubs and [[Spoil Five]], or to the value of the cards contained in taken tricks, as in '''point-trick games''' such as [[Pinochle]], the [[Tarot card games|Tarot]] family, [[Mariage (card game)|Mariage]], [[Rook (card game)|Rook]], [[All Fours]], [[Manille]], [[Briscola]], and most evasion games like [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]].<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|2008|pages=xvii\u2013xviii}}.</ref> The domino game [[42 (dominoes)|Texas 42]] is an example of a trick-taking game that is not a card game. '''Trick-and-draw games''' are trick-taking games in which the players can fill up their hands after each trick. In most variants, players are free to play any card into a trick in the first phase of the game, but must ''follow suit'' as soon as the stock is depleted. '''Trick-avoidance games''' like [[Reversis]] or [[Polignac (card game)|Polignac]] are those in which the aim is to  avoid taking some or all tricks.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest [[card game]]s were trick-taking games (as evidenced by the rank-and-[[Suit (cards)|suit]] structure) originating from China and spreading westwards during the early part of the second millennium. [[Michael Dummett]] noted that these games share various features. They were played without [[trump (card games)|trumps]], following suit was not required but only the highest card of the suit led wins, rotation was counter-clockwise, they were plain-trick games, and that the [[pip card]]s of one or more suit are in reverse order so that the lower cards beat the higher ones.<ref name=\"DummettGame\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qqm1AAAAIAAJ |title=The Game of Tarot: From Ferrara to Salt Lake City |isbn=9780715610145 |author1=Dummett |first1=Michael A. E |last2=Mann |first2=Sylvia |year=1980}}</ref> Two revolutions occurred in European trick-taking games that would lead to the development of ever more sophisticated card games. The first is the invention of trumps (and following suit to contain their power) in the 15th century. The second was [[bidding]] in the 17th century.\n\nAccording to card game researcher [[David Parlett]], the oldest known European trick-taking game, [[Karn\u00f6ffel]], was mentioned in 1426 in the Bavarian town [[N\u00f6rdlingen]] \u2013 roughly half a century after the introduction of playing cards to Europe, which were first mentioned in Spain in 1371.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|pages=35, 164}}.</ref> The oldest known \"trumps\" appear in Karn\u00f6ffel, where specific ranks of one suit were named ''Karn\u00f6ffel, Devil, Pope'' etc. and subject to an elaborate system of trumping powers. Around 1440 in Italy,  special cards called ''[[Trionfi (cards)|trionfi]]'' were introduced with a similar function. These special cards are now known as ''tarots'', and a deck augmented by tarots as a [[tarot]] deck. The trionfi/tarots formed essentially a fifth suit without the ordinary ranks but consisting of trumps in a fixed hierarchy. But one can get a similar effect by declaring all cards of a fixed or randomly determined suit to be trumps. This method, originating with [[Triomphe]], is still followed by a number of modern trick-taking games that do not involve an auction.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|pages=163\u2013165}}.</ref> Trumps were retroactively added to some games, such as [[Trappola]]. It is much rarer for trumps to be removed.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McLeod|first1=John|title=Playing the Game: Austrian Calling Games|journal=[[The Playing-Card]]|date=2013|volume=41|issue=4|pages=235\u2013238}}</ref><ref>McLeod, John. [http://www.pagat.com/marriage/anrufen.html#graden K\u00f6nigrufen (Graden)] at [[pagat.com]]. Retrieved 25 January 2016.</ref> The invention of trumps became so popular that very few European trick-taking games exist without them. This did not stop the two-handed [[Piquet]] from becoming the most popular card game in Europe during the 16th century. Parlett suggests the invention of trumps let players in games involving more than two a greater chance of heading a trick.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|pages=180}}</ref>\n\nThe invention of bidding for a trump suit is credited to [[Ombre]], the most popular card game of the 17th century. Rather than having a randomly selected trump suit, players can now hold an auction for it. The most popular games of the 18th-century was tarot which experienced a great revival.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|page=300}}.</ref> During this time, many tarot games borrowed bidding over the stock (taroc-l'hombre). In the 20th century, Whist (now with bidding and the dummy hand) developed into [[Contract bridge]], the last global trick-taking game.\n\nIt is possible that the origin of the practice of counting tricks (in plain-trick games) was the counting of cards won in tricks. It was therefore a logical development to accord some cards a higher counting-value, and some cards no value at all, leading to point-trick games. Point-trick games are at least as old as tarot decks and may even predate the invention of trumps. [[Elfern]] and [[F\u00fcnfzehnern]] are possible candidates although the earliest references date to the 19th century. Nearly all point-trick games are played with tarot decks or [[stripped deck]]s, which in many countries became standard before 1600, and neither point-trick games nor stripped decks have a tradition in England.\n\nWhile there are a number of games with unusual card-point values, such as [[Trappola]] and [[All Fours]], most point-trick games are in the huge family of [[Ace\u2013Ten card games]] beginning with [[Brusquembille]]. [[Pinochle]] is a representative of this family that is popular in the United States. Other examples include [[Belote]] and [[Skat (card game)|Skat]].\n\nIn contrast to Europe, Chinese trick-taking games did not develop trumps or bidding. They diverged into multi-trick games where melds can only be beaten by other melds provided they have the same number of cards. During the [[Qing dynasty]], these multi-trick games evolved into the earliest draw-and-discard games where the players' objective is to form melds and \"go out\" rather than capturing the opponents' cards. [[Khanhoo]] is an example of a multi-trick game that became a draw-and-discard game.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Berry|first1=John|title=Chinese Money-Suited Cards|journal=[[The Playing-Card]]|date=2003|volume=31|issue=5|pages=230\u2013235}}</ref> Multi-trick games are also probably the source for climbing games like [[Winner (card game)|Winner]] and ''[[dou dizhu]]'' which first appeared during the [[Cultural Revolution]].\n\n==Basic structure==\nCertain actions in trick-taking games with three or more players always proceed in the same direction. In games originating in North and West Europe, including England, Russia, and the United States and Canada, the rotation is typically clockwise (i.e., play proceeds to the left); in South and East Europe, Latin America, and Asia it is typically counterclockwise, so that play proceeds to the right. When games move from one region to another, they tend to initially preserve their original sense of rotation, but a region with a dominant sense of rotation may adapt a migrated game to its own sensibilities.<!--This should be enough. It's easy to guess the rotation in former colonies from this.--> For two-player games the order of play is moot as either direction would result in exactly the same turn order.\n\nIn each ''hand'' or ''deal'', one player is the ''[[Dealer (card player)|dealer]]''. This function moves from deal to deal in the normal direction of play. The dealer usually [[Shuffling|shuffles]] the deck (some games use \"soft shuffling\", where the dealer does not explicitly shuffle the deck), and after giving the player one seat from the dealer opposite the normal direction of play an opportunity to [[Cut (cards)|cut]], hands out the same (prescribed) number of cards to each player, usually in an order following the normal direction of play. Most games deal cards one at a time in rotation; a few games require dealing multiple cards at one time in a ''packet''. The cards apportioned to each player are collectively known as that player's ''hand'' and are only known to the player. Some games involve a set of cards that are not dealt to a player's hand; these cards form the ''stock'' (see below). It is generally good manners to leave one's cards on the table until the deal is complete.\n\nThe player sitting one seat after the declarer (one with the highest bid and not the dealer) in normal rotation is known as the ''[[eldest hand]]'', also called the ''forehand'' in [[Skat (card game)|Skat]] and other games of German origin. The eldest hand ''leads'' to the first ''trick'', i.e. places the first card of the trick face up in the middle of all players. The other players each follow with a single card, in the direction of play. When every player has played a card to the trick, the trick is evaluated to determine the winner, who takes the cards, places them face down on a pile, and leads to the next trick. The winner or taker of a trick is usually the player who played the highest-value card of the suit that was led, unless the game uses one or more ''[[Trump (card games)|trump]]'' cards (see below).\n\nThe player who leads to a trick is usually allowed to play an arbitrary card from their hand. Some games have restrictions on the first card played in the hand, or may disallow leading a card of a particular [[suit (cards)|suit]] until that suit has been played \"off-suit\" in a prior trick (called \"breaking\" the suit, usually seen in cases of a trump or penalty suit). Other games have special restrictions on the card that must be led to the first trick; usually this is a specific card (e.g., 2{{Clubs}}) and the holder of that card is the eldest hand instead of the person one seat after the dealer.\n\nIn many games, the following players must ''[[#Follow suit|follow suit]]'' if they can, i.e., they must play a card of the same suit if possible. A player who cannot follow suit may ''sluff'' a card, i.e., play a card of a different suit. A trick is won by the player who has played the highest-ranked card of the ''suit led'', i.e., of the suit of the first card in the trick (unless the game uses a [[#Trumps|trump suit]]).\n\nIt can be an advantage to lead to a trick, because the player who leads controls the suit that is led and which others must follow; the leading player playing a suit of which he has many, decreases the chance that anyone else would be able to follow suit; while conversely playing a suit of which he has few, allows him to rid his hand of that suit (known as ''[[Void (cards)|voiding]]'' the suit), freeing him from the restriction to follow suit when that suit is led by another player. On the other hand, it can also be advantageous to be the final player who plays to the trick, because at that point one has full information about the other cards played to the trick; the last player to a trick can play a card just slightly higher or lower than the current winning card, guaranteeing they will win or lose it by the minimum amount necessary, saving more valuable high or low value cards for situations where they must guarantee that a card played early to a trick will win or lose.\n\nWhen all cards have been played, the number or contents of the tricks won by each player is tallied and used to update the score. Scoring based on the play of tricks varies widely between games, but in most games either the number of tricks a player or partnership has won (''plain-trick'' games), or the value of certain cards that the player has won by taking tricks (''point-trick'' games) is important.\n\n== Partnerships ==\n* In many games such as [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]] and [[Oh Hell]], all players play individually against each other.\n* In many four-player games such as [[Contract bridge|Bridge]], [[Euchre]] and [[Spades (card game)|Spades]], the players sitting opposite to each other form a fixed partnership.\n* Some games such as [[Pinochle]] are commonly played with or without partnerships, depending on the number of players.\n* In some contract/auction games for three or more players, e.g. most Tarot variants, the contractor (''declarer'' or ''taker'') plays alone against all opponents, who form an ''ad hoc'' partnership (the ''defenders'').\n* In some games the partnerships are decided by chance \u2013 the contractor forms a partnership with the winner of the first trick, or with the player who holds a certain card. This practice originated from Cinquillo and [[Quadrille (card game)|Quadrille]].\n** In [[K\u00f6nigrufen]] and five-player [[French tarot]] the taker can call out a suit of which he does not possess the King, and is partnered with whomever does have it against the other three.\n** Standard [[Schafkopf]] is similar: A \"player\" can \"call\" a suit, and the person holding the ace of that suit becomes his partner for the hand. As this is not openly declared, it can be a challenge for the remaining players, to find out who is partnered with whom through cunning playing for several tricks. Aside from that, standard Schafkopf also has several solo options, where the \"player\" plays alone against the rest.\n** In [[Doppelkopf]] the two players holding the black Queens are partners for that hand. Special rules are provided for the case where a single player holds both black Queens.\n\n==Stock==\nIn some games not all cards are distributed to the players, and a ''stock'' remains. This stock can be referred to by different names, depending on the game; ''supply'', ''talon'', ''nest'', ''skat'', ''kitty'', and ''dog'' are common game-specific and/or regional names.\n\nIn some games the stock remains untouched throughout play of the hand; it is simply a pile of \"extra\" cards that will never be played and whose values are unknown, which will reduce the effectiveness of \"[[Card reading (bridge)|counting cards]]\" (a common strategy of keeping track of the cards that have been played or are yet to be played). In games without bidding, trumps may be decided by exposing a card in the stock as in [[Triomphe]]. In other games, the winner of an auction-bidding process (the taker or declarer) may get to exchange cards from his hand with the stock, either by integrating the stock into his hand and then discarding equal cards as in [[Skat (card game)|Skat]], [[Rook (card game)|Rook]] and [[French tarot]], or in a \"blind\" fashion by discarding and drawing as in [[Ombre]]. The stock, either in its original or discarded form, may additionally form part of one or more players' \"scoring piles\" of tricks taken; it may be kept by the declarer, may be won by the player of the first trick, or may go to an opposing player or partnership.\n\nIn some games, especially two-player games, after each trick every player draws a new card. This continues while the stock lasts. Since this drawing mechanism would normally make it difficult or impossible to detect a revoke (for instance, the player may not be able to follow suit, so they play off-suit and then immediately draw a card of the suit led), in the first phase of trick-play (before the stock is empty) players generally need not follow suit. A widespread game of this type is the [[Marriage group]].\n\n== Bidding ==\n\nIn a ''contract'' game the winning and scoring conditions are not fixed but are chosen by one of the players after seeing their hand. In such games, players make ''bids'' depending on the number of tricks or card points they believe they can win during play of the hand. One or more of these bids stands as the ''contract'', and the player who made that bid is rewarded for meeting it or penalized for not meeting it.\n\nIn ''auction'' games, bidding players are competing against each other for the right to attempt to make the contract. In a few games, the contract is fixed (normally a simple majority, less often based on certain cards captured during play) and players' bids are a wager of game points to be won or lost. In others, the bid is a number of tricks or card points the bidder is confident that they or their partnership will take. Either of these can also include the suit to be used as trumps during the hand. Common bids include slam (winning all the tricks), [[mis\u00e8re]] (losing all the tricks), ouvert (the contractor's hand is exposed), playing without using the stock or only part of it, and winning the last trick or other specific tricks. The highest bid becomes the contract and the highest bidder is the ''contractor'', known in some games as the ''declarer'' or ''taker'', who then plays either with or without a partner. The other players become ''opponents'' or ''defenders'', whose main goal is to prevent the contract being met. They may announce a ''contra'' against the contractor which doubles the points for the hand. The contractor can declare a ''recontra'' which will double the points again.\n\nPopular examples of games with auctions include [[Contract bridge]], [[Pinochle]], [[Tarot card games|tarot games]], [[Skat (card game)|Skat]], [[Belote]] and [[Twenty-eight (card game)|Twenty-Eight]]. In many auction games the eldest hand leads to the first trick, regardless of who won the auction, but in some, such as [[Contract bridge|Contract Bridge]], the first lead is made by the player next in rotation after the contractor, so that the contractor plays last to that trick.\n\nIn ''precision'' or ''exact-prediction'' games, all players choose their winning condition independently: to win precisely a predicted number of tricks ([[Oh Hell]]) or card points ([[Jass|Differenzler]]). Each player's bid stands (in partnership games the partners' bids are often combined), and each player or partnership then tries to take exactly the number of tricks or points they bid, and are rewarded or penalized for doing so independently of anyone else's success or failure in meeting their bid. This type of game began to mature in the 20th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|pages=311\u2013315}}.</ref> Other games generally falling into the exact-prediction category are [[Spades (card game)|Spades]] and [[Ninety-nine (trick-taking card game)|Ninety-Nine]].\n\n==Trumps==\n''[[Trump (card games)|Trump cards]]'' are a set of one or more cards in the deck that, when played, are of higher value than the suit led. If a trick contains any trump cards, it is won by the highest-value trump card played, not the highest-value card of the suit led.\n\nIn most games with trumps, one of the four suits is identified as the ''trump suit''. In the simplest case, there is a static trump suit such as the Spade suit in the game [[Spades (card game)|Spades]], or a dedicated trump suit in the [[Tarot card games|Tarot]] family (in addition to the other four) is featured. More often, a dynamic trump suit is determined by some means, either randomly by selection of a card as in [[Oh Hell]] and the original form of [[Whist]], or decided by the winner or winning bid of an auction as in [[contract bridge]] and some forms of [[Pinochle]]. In certain games, such as Rowboat and Rage, the trump suit may change during the course of the hand, even from trick to trick. Some psychological variety is added to the game and makes it more difficult to cheat if the trump suit is only chosen after dealing.\n\nIn some games, in addition to or separately from a trump suit, certain fixed cards are always the highest trumps, e.g. the Jacks in [[Skat (card game)|Skat]], the Jacks or Jokers in [[Euchre]], and the Rook Bird card in [[Rook (card game)|Rook]]. They are called ''matadors'' after the high trumps in [[Ombre]]. ''Matadors'' either have high point values or special abilities as in [[Spoil Five]] where they can revoke legally.\n\nSome games have more than one trump suit, such as the quasi-trick game [[Stortok]], in which there are two trumps, with one superseding the other. Other games have no trumps; [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]] for instance has no provision for a trump suit of any kind (the Hearts suit for which the game is named has a different significance). Though trump is part of [[contract bridge]], teams can make bids that do not specify a trump suit, and if that is the winning bid then there is no trump suit for that hand (making such a contract is regarded as harder to accomplish).\n\n==Declarations==\nIn some games such as [[Piquet]], [[Tarocchini]], and [[Belote]], before the taking of tricks commences, players can expose certain cards or [[Meld (cards)|melds]] (combinations) that they possess for bonus points. While this phase may seem to award players for pure chance, those who do declare risk letting their opponents develop strategies to counter the cards that they have revealed.\n\n==Follow suit==\nIn many games, ''following suit'' is the obligatory action of playing a card of the same suit as that of the leading suit. A player must follow suit if that player has cards of the leading suit in his hands. There is a large variation of strictness in following suit among games.<ref>McLeod, John. [https://www.pagat.com/mech.html#followsuit Mechanics of Card Games] at [[pagat.com]]. Retrieved 18 February 2017.</ref>\n\nIn most modern games with trump suits, the rules for following suit do not distinguish between the trump suit and the ''plain suits''. If a trick begins with a plain suit card and a later player cannot follow suit, the player may choose freely to either ''slough'' (discard a card of another plain suit), or ''ruff'' (''trump'' the trick by playing a trump card). Subsequent players to the trick must still follow the original suit, and may only discard or trump if they do not hold a card of the suit led. Certain games are \"play to beat\" or \"must-trump\"; if a player cannot follow suit but can play trump, they must play trump, and additionally if they are able they must beat any trump card already played to the trick. [[Pinochle]] and several of the [[Tarot card games]] have this rule.\n\nSome games, notably [[French tarot]] and a variation of [[Rook (card game)|Rook]], use a special card (in French Tarot's case, the [[The Fool (Tarot card)|Excuse]]) that can be played at any time. If not, he has the choice of playing a trump to possibly win the trick, or rough (waste) a different suit.\n\nIf unable to follow suit or trump, any card can be played. Each trick must contain one card per player, and hence a player unable to satisfy any other instruction is at liberty to play any card. Usually a low-ranking card or one from a short suit is sacrificed. The former is used to protect a higher ranking card while the latter is to help void a suit so as to allow trumping a future trick.\n\nIt is also possible that the specific deal has \"no trump\". In that case, any card other than the leading suit played has no value, in most trick-taking games. In some games such as [[Oh, hell]], where the player may need to not get more tricks to win, playing cards other than the leading suit can be useful.<ref>McLeod, John. [http://www.pagat.com/exact/ohhell.html Oh Hell!] at [[pagat.com]]. Retrieved 18 February 2017.</ref>\n\nFor example, consider the following [[Whist]] hand:\n:: Trump diamonds {{cards|d}}\n* North: {{cards|As|Ks|4h|9d}}\n* East: {{cards|7s|5d|Qc|10c}}\n* South: {{cards|3h|2d|Jd|Ac}}\n* West: {{cards|5s|2s|6h|5c}}\n\nNorth leads the deal with {{spades|K}}. Now, all the other players must follow suit, i.e. play a spade card. East has a spade card, and thus must follow suit by playing {{spades|7}}. South, however, does not have any spade card, and thus is allowed to play any card he wants. If he desires to win the trick, he can override North's {{spades|K}} by playing a diamond card (diamond being the trump), for example {{diamonds|J}}. If he does not want to win the trick, he can slough any other suit, such as {{hearts|3}}. Let us assume that he plays {{diamonds|J}}, overriding North's card. Now, West still has to follow suit, since he has a spade card, and plays {{spades|2}}. South's trump card, gives him an opportunity to escape following suit, and he wins the trick.\n\nIf a player who can follow suit does not do so, or in games with additional restrictions on card play, not following these restrictions is known as a [[revoke]], or 'renege'. A revoke typically cannot be discovered at the time when it is committed, but when a player plays off-suit to a trick, competent opponents will make a mental note that the player does not hold the suit led, and will notice later if the player later plays a card of the suit they were thought to be void in. The situation is similar for other types of revoke. Most game rules prescribe a severe penalty for a revoke and may also result in the hand being voided (a \"misdeal\"). Decks of cards have been marketed for trick-taking games with the traditional French suit symbols, but in four colors; these are often called [[Four-color deck|\"no-revoke\" decks]], as the color contrast between each suit makes a potential revoking play easier to spot and harder to do accidentally.\n\nIn some trick games\u2014typically ones in which players are not penalized for winning tricks, and there is no requirement for trumping or following suit when possible\u2014players may ''slough'', or play a card face down.  A card so played is incapable of winning the trick; but sloughing has the advantage that the other players cannot see what card is played. As this form of sloughing has the potential to be used to cheat in most games (i.e. playing a winning card face-down to avoid taking an \"overtrick\" or a trick containing penalty points) and is thus not allowed, ''sloughing'' in the vernacular more often refers to simply discarding an off-suit card on a trick, particularly one that could be dangerous to that player if kept. This form of sloughing is important in evasion games and in some contract games where \"overtricks\" are penalized; in [[Oh Hell]], for instance, a player who cannot follow suit may elect to discard a card that would win if played to follow suit later, thus reducing the chance that the player will \"bag\", or take more tricks than needed. This is common in [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]], where high-value cards (especially Spades and Hearts) are dangerous as they increase the chance of winning a trick with penalty points.\n\nSome games such as [[Pinochle]] use several decks shuffled together. In these games, there may be several equal winning cards in a trick; such games then use other rules to break ties. Common rules include:\n* the first-played of the tying cards wins\n* the last-played of the tying cards wins\n* The tying cards cancel each other out, and the trick is taken by the next-highest card that was played.\n* The tying cards cancel each other out, but the trick is spoiled (ignored).\n\nA common additional rule to reduce these occurrences is that a player cannot play a card tying the current high card unless they would renege or fail to overtrump by making any other play.\n\n==Scoring==\nWhen all tricks have been played, the winner of the hand and the players' scores can be determined. The determining factor in plain-trick games (the most popular form of trick-taking games in English-speaking countries) is simply how many tricks each player or partnership has taken. In point-trick games, certain card values are worth varying points, and the players sum the points from cards in their \"scoring piles\" that were accumulated by taking tricks. Points for cards, and the method of counting points, vary by game; in Rook, for example, the 5-card of each color is worth 5 points, the 10 and 14 (or Ace) is worth 10, and the Rook Bird (or Joker) is worth 20, while all other cards are worth nothing. Many Chinese card games like Finding Friends use a very similar system, in which each 5-card is worth 5 points, and the 10 and King are each worth 10 points.<ref>Rules for Chinese trick-taking card game [http://www.zhao-pengyou.com/ \"Finding Friends (Zhao Pengyou)\"]. Retrieved on 7 September 2018.</ref> Pinochle has many popular scoring variants usually based on point values for face cards and Aces, while pip cards score no points. In French Tarot, all cards have a value including a half-point, and are traditionally scored in pairs of a high-value and a low-value card which results in a whole-point value for the pair.\n\nIn the most common ''positive'' or ''race'' games, players seek to win as many tricks or card points as possible. To win a hand, a player typically needs to win a minimal number of tricks or card points; this minimal threshold is usually called the \"contract\", and may be defined by the game's rules (a simple majority of total available points or tricks, or tiered thresholds depending on which player or side has captured certain cards), or the result of an \"auction\" or \"bidding\" process. A player who wins more than the number of tricks or card points necessary for winning the hand may be rewarded with a higher score, or conversely (in exact-prediction games) they may be penalized.\n\nThere are also ''negative'' or ''evasion'' games, in which the object is to avoid tricks or card points. E.g. in Hearts each card point won in a trick contributes negatively to the score. A special type is ''mis\u00e8re'' games, which are usually variants of positive games which can only be won by not winning a single trick.\n\nOther criteria also occur. Sometimes the last trick has special significance. In ''marriage games'' such as Pinochle the winner of the last trick receives 10 points in addition to the card points, while in ''final-trick'' games such as [[c\u1eaft t\u00ea]] only the winner of the last trick can win a hand. There are also blends between positive and negative games, e.g. the aim may be to win a certain prescribed number of tricks. Many card games, regardless of their normal scoring mechanism, give bonuses to players or partnerships who win all tricks or possible points in a hand, or conversely lose all tricks or points.\n\nGames usually end after every player has had an equal chance to be the dealer. The number of rotations varies widely among games. Some games have a cumulative score where all points from each hand add up. Others assign only a set number of game points for winning a hand. For example, a player or side that wins one hand may be awarded one game point, two if they achieve a slam. The player or side with the most game points or the first to reach a certain number of card or game points, is considered the winner.\n\n==Special variations==\n=== Variations to basic rules ===\nNumerous further variations to the basic rules may occur, and only a few examples can be mentioned here:\n* Certain games require the holder of a certain card value to play it as the lead to the first trick of a hand; [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]], as commonly played in North America, requires the player holding the 2{{Clubs}} to play it as the lead-off card. Variants of [[Pinochle]] sometimes require the first player to the left of the dealer that holds a ''dix'' (9{{Clubs}}) to lead off.\n* There may be restrictions on leading certain suits; a common Hearts rule is that a player may not lead a Heart until at least one trick has had a Heart played off-suit to another trick. Spades has a similar but less-common variation regarding its trump suit.\n* There are trick-taking games played with [[Domino]] tiles instead of playing cards. These include the Chinese [[Tien Gow]] and [[42 (dominoes)|Texas 42]]. [[Giog]] is played with [[Xiangqi|Chinese chess]] tiles.\n* Many games are played with one or more ''[[stripped deck]]s'' (a deck from which certain card values are removed). The most common stripped deck is a [[piquet deck]], used for [[piquet]], [[Belote]], [[Skat (card game)|Skat]], [[Euchre]], [[Bezique]] and (with two piquet decks) [[Pinochle]], among others. [[Rook (card game)|Rook]]'s main variant, Kentucky Discard, uses the equivalent of a 52-card deck with all card values 2\u20134 removed. Most regional [[Tarot]] variants, especially Central European and Italian variants like Tarock and Tarocco, use some subset of the \"full\" 78-card Tarot deck.\n* In Bridge the partner of the contractor or ''declarer'' is called ''dummy'' and does not actively participate in the play; dummy's hand is instead laid on the table face-up after the opening lead, and declarer chooses the cards from dummy's hand to play during dummy's turns.\n* In [[Karuta#Unsun Karuta|Hachinin-meri]] and Truf, trumps are played face down. When the trick is finished, the trumps are revealed to see who won the trick.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Depaulis|first1=Thierry|title=Unsun, a Far-eastern Cousin of Ombre|journal=[[The Playing-Card]]|date=1983|volume=12|issue=1|pages=39\u201344}}</ref><ref>McLeod, John. [http://www.pagat.com/exact/truf.html Truf] at [[pagat.com]]. Retrieved 25 January 2016.</ref>\n* In many trumpless games that do not require following suit, sluffing is done face down. This is done in [[Madiao]], [[Tien Gow]], [[Tam c\u00fac]], [[:zh:\u516d\u864e\u724c|Six Tigers]], [[Ganjifa]], [[Kaiserspiel]], and Brazilian [[Truco]].\n* Some cards lose their trick-taking power if they are not led or played in a specific trick as in [[Karn\u00f6ffel]], [[Tien Gow]], and [[Ganjifa]].\n* In [[tarot game]]s played outside of Central Europe, [[The Fool (Tarot card)|the Fool]] is a special card that excuses the player from following suit. Except in rare circumstances in some games, it can neither capture nor be captured. Usually a non-counting card is given as compensation to the trick's winner by the Fool's owner.\n\n=== Rules in Austrian and German games ===\nIn games derived from Austria and Germany, trick-taking is governed by the rules called ''Zw\u00e4nge''. The three main ones are ''Farbzwang'', ''Stichzwang'' and ''Trumpfzwang''. Although they broadly equate to rules in English-speaking countries, there are no single-word equivalents. For many games of this type, applying these rules correctly is crucial to the type of contract being played.\n\n==== ''Farbzwang'' ====\n''Farbzwang'' (or ''Bedienzwang'') literally means \"suit compulsion\" and is the rule that players must follow the suit of the first card to be led to the trick, provided that they have a card of that suit. If a player does not have a card of the led suit, they may play ('discard') a card of their choice. If a player has several cards of the led suit, they may choose which to play. In most cases it makes sense to play a higher ranking card.\n\n==== ''Stichzwang'' ====\n''Stichzwang'' means \"trick compulsion\" and is the rule that players must attempt to win the trick if they are able, either by playing a higher card of the led suit or by playing a trump card.\n\n==== ''Farbzwang'' with ''Stichzwang'' ====\nSome games apply ''Farbzwang'' and ''Stichzwang'' together, which means that a player, when it is his turn, must:\n* take the trick with a higher card of the led suit. If unable to do so, he must\n* discard a lower card of the led suit. If that is not possible, he must\n* take the trick with a trump card, but if that is also not feasible, he may\n* discard a card of his choice.\n\n''Farbzwang'', the requirement to follow suit, always takes precedence over ''Stichzwang''. A player is not allowed to take the trick with a trump if he can follow suit.\n\n==== ''Trumpfzwang'' ====\n''Trumpzwang'' means \"trump compulsion\" and requires that a player ''must'' play a trump if he cannot follow suit. In other words, he may not simply discard, if he cannot follow suit.\n\n''Example'': Acorns are trumps. Forehand plays the 8 of Bells, middlehand trumps with a 10 of Acorns; rearhand has no Bells, but does have a trump card, the 8 of Acorns. He must play this and cannot discard another non-trump card in order to keep the trump for a subsequent trick.\n\n==== ''Tarockzwang'' ====\n''Tarockzwang'' is used in [[tarock game]]s such as [[K\u00f6nigrufen]] and [[Tapp-Tarock]] and means \"Tarock compulsion\" or the requirement to play a Tarock card if one is led to the trick or if a player is unable to follow suit. It is a form of ''Trumpfzwang''.\n\n== Examples ==\n{{Related article|List of Ace-Ten games}}\nTrick-taking games may be divided into point-trick games and plain-trick games. Examples of each are as follows:\n\n=== Point-trick games ===\nPoint-trick game are those in which win or loss is determined by the total value of the \"counters\" in the tricks.<ref name=\"parlett,2008,644\u2013645\">{{harvnb|Parlett|2008|pages=644\u2013645}}.</ref> The counters are cards with a point value, sometimes referred to as \"card points\" to avoid confusion with \"game points\" awarded for winning the game and/or bonuses.\n\nExamples include:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20}}\n* [[Bavarian Tarock]]\n* [[Belote]]\n* [[B\u00e9zique]]\n* [[Binokel]]\n* [[Doppelkopf]]\n* [[Jass]]\n* Finding Friends ([[Zhao Pengyou]])\n* [[Schafkopf]]\n* [[Schnapsen]] or [[Sixty-six (card game)|Sixty-six]]\n* [[Skat (card game)|Skat]]\n* [[Tarock]] games ([[French tarot]], [[K\u00f6nigrufen]], [[Zwanzigerrufen]], etc.)\n* [[Trappola]] (Bulka)\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n=== Plain-trick games ===\nPlain-trick games are those in which the outcome is determined by the number of tricks taken, regardless of their content.<ref name=\"parlett,2008,644\u2013645\"/>\n\nExamples of plain-trick games include:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20}}\n* [[Boston (card game)|Boston]]\n* [[Bridge (card game)|Bridge]]\n* [[\u00c9cart\u00e9]]\n* [[Jabberwocky (card game)|Jabberwocky]]\n* [[Ombre]] and [[Quadrille (card game)|Quadrille]]\n* [[Piquet]]\n* [[Pr\u00e9f\u00e9rence]]\n* [[Solo Whist]]\n* [[Tippen]]\n* [[Watten (card game)|Watten]]\n* [[Whist]]\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\nIn games that consist of several successive, different, trick-taking contracts, such as Herzeln or Quodlibet, it is not possible to categorise them as either point- or plain-trick games.\n\n=== Trick-avoidance games ===\nTrick-avoidance games are those in which the aim is to avoid taking certain tricks or to avoid taking all tricks. [[Misere]] or [[Bettel (cards)|bettel]] are contracts in which the declarer undertakes to win no tricks. There are also contracts like [[Piccolo (cards)|Piccolo]] in which the aim is to take only one trick. Examples include:\n\n* [[Bassadewitz]]\n* [[Grasobern]]\n* [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]]\n* [[Polignac (card game)|Polignac]]\n* [[Slobberhannes]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of trick-taking games]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Citation\n|last1=Dummett\n|first1=Michael\n|last2=Mann\n|first2=Sylvia\n|title=The Game of Tarot: From Ferrara to Salt Lake City\n|year=1980\n|publisher=Duckworth\n|isbn=9780715610145}}\n* {{Citation\n|last1=Kastner\n|first1=Hugo\n|last2=Folkvord\n|first2=Gerald K.\n|title=Die gro\u00dfe Humboldt Enzyklop\u00e4die der Kartenspiele\n|year=2005\n|publisher=Humboldt\n|language=German\n|isbn=978-3-89994-058-9}}\n* {{Citation\n|editor-last=McLeod\n|editor-first=John\n|title=Card Games website\n|url=http://www.pagat.com/}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Parlett\n|first=David\n|title=The Oxford guide to card games: a historical survey\n|year=1990\n|publisher=Oxford University Press\n|isbn=978-0-19-214165-1\n|url-access=registration\n|url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordguidetocar00parl\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Parlett\n|first=David\n|title=The Penguin Book of Card Games\n|year=2008\n|edition=3rd\n|publisher=Penguin Books\n|isbn=978-0-14-103787-5}}.\n\n{{List of trick-taking games}}\n{{Tarot and Tarock card games}}\n\n[[Category:Card game terminology]]\n[[Category:Trick-taking games| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{more sources|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:Four overlapping playing cards.jpg|thumb|<center>'''A trick'''</center><br><small>North led the 10{{Spades}}. Usually all players must ''follow suit'' and play a spade unless they have none. East does so with the K{{spades}}. South doesn't have a spade, he plays the J{{diamonds}}, and West the 7{{hearts}}. In a notrump game, East wins the trick, having played the highest card of the suit led (unless the game is an [[Ace-Ten games|Ace-Ten game]], with 10 being higher than the King, making North win the trick). However, if diamonds or hearts are trumps, South or West respectively win.</small>]]\nA '''trick-taking game''' is a [[card game|card]] or [[tile-based game]] in which play of a ''[[Hand (card games)|hand]]'' centers on a series of finite rounds or units of play, called ''tricks'', which are each evaluated to determine a winner or ''taker'' of that trick. The object of such games then may be closely tied to the number of tricks taken, as in '''plain-trick games''' such as [[Whist]], [[Contract bridge]], [[Spades (card game)|Spades]], [[Napoleon (card game)|Napoleon]], [[Euchre]], Rowboat, Clubs and [[Spoil Five]], or to the value of the cards contained in taken tricks, as in '''point-trick games''' such as [[Pinochle]], the [[Tarot card games|Tarot]] family, [[Mariage (card game)|Mariage]], [[Rook (card game)|Rook]], [[All Fours]], [[Manille]], [[Briscola]], and most evasion games like [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]].<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|2008|pages=xvii\u2013xviii}}.</ref> The domino game [[42 (dominoes)|Texas 42]] is an example of a trick-taking game that is not a card game. '''Trick-and-draw games''' are trick-taking games in which the players can fill up their hands after each trick. In most variants, players are free to play any card into a trick in the first phase of the game, but must ''follow suit'' as soon as the stock is depleted. '''Trick-avoidance games''' like [[Reversis]] or [[Polignac (card game)|Polignac]] are those in which the aim is to  avoid taking some or all tricks.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest [[card game]]s were trick-taking games (as evidenced by the rank-and-[[Suit (cards)|suit]] structure) originating from China and spreading westwards during the early part of the second millennium. [[Michael Dummett]] noted that these games share various features. They were played without [[trump (card games)|trumps]], following suit was not required but only the highest card of the suit led wins, rotation was counter-clockwise, they were plain-trick games, and that the [[pip card]]s of one or more suit are in reverse order so that the lower cards beat the higher ones.<ref name=\"DummettGame\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qqm1AAAAIAAJ |title=The Game of Tarot: From Ferrara to Salt Lake City |isbn=9780715610145 |author1=Dummett |first1=Michael A. E |last2=Mann |first2=Sylvia |year=1980}}</ref> Two revolutions occurred in European trick-taking games that would lead to the development of ever more sophisticated card games. The first is the invention of trumps (and following suit to contain their power) in the 15th century. The second was [[bidding]] in the 17th century.\n\nAccording to card game researcher [[David Parlett]], the oldest known European trick-taking game, [[Karn\u00f6ffel]], was mentioned in 1426 in the Bavarian town [[N\u00f6rdlingen]] \u2013 roughly half a century after the introduction of playing cards to Europe, which were first mentioned in Spain in 1371.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|pages=35, 164}}.</ref> The oldest known \"trumps\" appear in Karn\u00f6ffel, where specific ranks of one suit were named ''Karn\u00f6ffel, Devil, Pope'' etc. and subject to an elaborate system of trumping powers. Around 1440 in Italy,  special cards called ''[[Trionfi (cards)|trionfi]]'' were introduced with a similar function. These special cards are now known as ''tarots'', and a deck augmented by tarots as a [[tarot]] deck. The trionfi/tarots formed essentially a fifth suit without the ordinary ranks but consisting of trumps in a fixed hierarchy. But one can get a similar effect by declaring all cards of a fixed or randomly determined suit to be trumps. This method, originating with [[Triomphe]], is still followed by a number of modern trick-taking games that do not involve an auction.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|pages=163\u2013165}}.</ref> Trumps were retroactively added to some games, such as [[Trappola]]. It is much rarer for trumps to be removed.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McLeod|first1=John|title=Playing the Game: Austrian Calling Games|journal=[[The Playing-Card]]|date=2013|volume=41|issue=4|pages=235\u2013238}}</ref><ref>McLeod, John. [http://www.pagat.com/marriage/anrufen.html#graden K\u00f6nigrufen (Graden)] at [[pagat.com]]. Retrieved 25 January 2016.</ref> The invention of trumps became so popular that very few European trick-taking games exist without them. This did not stop the two-handed [[Piquet]] from becoming the most popular card game in Europe during the 16th century. Parlett suggests the invention of trumps let players in games involving more than two a greater chance of heading a trick.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|pages=180}}</ref>\n\nThe invention of bidding for a trump suit is credited to [[Ombre]], the most popular card game of the 17th century. Rather than having a randomly selected trump suit, players can now hold an auction for it. The most popular games of the 18th-century was tarot which experienced a great revival.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|page=300}}.</ref> During this time, many tarot games borrowed bidding over the stock (taroc-l'hombre). In the 20th century, Whist (now with bidding and the dummy hand) developed into [[Contract bridge]], the last global trick-taking game.\n\nIt is possible that the origin of the practice of counting tricks (in plain-trick games) was the counting of cards won in tricks. It was therefore a logical development to accord some cards a higher counting-value, and some cards no value at all, leading to point-trick games. Point-trick games are at least as old as tarot decks and may even predate the invention of trumps. [[Elfern]] and [[F\u00fcnfzehnern]] are possible candidates although the earliest references date to the 19th century. Nearly all point-trick games are played with tarot decks or [[stripped deck]]s, which in many countries became standard before 1600, and neither point-trick games nor stripped decks have a tradition in England.\n\nWhile there are a number of games with unusual card-point values, such as [[Trappola]] and [[All Fours]], most point-trick games are in the huge family of [[Ace\u2013Ten card games]] beginning with [[Brusquembille]]. [[Pinochle]] is a representative of this family that is popular in the United States. Other examples include [[Belote]] and [[Skat (card game)|Skat]].\n\nIn contrast to Europe, Chinese trick-taking games did not develop trumps or bidding. They diverged into multi-trick games where melds can only be beaten by other melds provided they have the same number of cards. During the [[Qing dynasty]], these multi-trick games evolved into the earliest draw-and-discard games where the players' objective is to form melds and \"go out\" rather than capturing the opponents' cards. [[Khanhoo]] is an example of a multi-trick game that became a draw-and-discard game.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Berry|first1=John|title=Chinese Money-Suited Cards|journal=[[The Playing-Card]]|date=2003|volume=31|issue=5|pages=230\u2013235}}</ref> Multi-trick games are also probably the source for climbing games like [[Winner (card game)|Winner]] and ''[[dou dizhu]]'' which first appeared during the [[Cultural Revolution]].\n\n==Basic structure==\nCertain actions in trick-taking games with three or more players always proceed in the same direction. In games originating in North and West Europe, including England, Russia, and the United States and Canada, the rotation is typically clockwise (i.e., play proceeds to the left); in South and East Europe, Latin America, and Asia it is typically counterclockwise, so that play proceeds to the right. When games move from one region to another, they tend to initially preserve their original sense of rotation, but a region with a dominant sense of rotation may adapt a migrated game to its own sensibilities.<!--This should be enough. It's easy to guess the rotation in former colonies from this.--> For two-player games the order of play is moot as either direction would result in exactly the same turn order.\n\nIn each ''hand'' or ''deal'', one player is the ''[[Dealer (card player)|dealer]]''. This function moves from deal to deal in the normal direction of play. The dealer usually [[Shuffling|shuffles]] the deck (some games use \"soft shuffling\", where the dealer does not explicitly shuffle the deck), and after giving the player one seat from the dealer opposite the normal direction of play an opportunity to [[Cut (cards)|cut]], hands out the same (prescribed) number of cards to each player, usually in an order following the normal direction of play. Most games deal cards one at a time in rotation; a few games require dealing multiple cards at one time in a ''packet''. The cards apportioned to each player are collectively known as that player's ''hand'' and are only known to the player. Some games involve a set of cards that are not dealt to a player's hand; these cards form the ''stock'' (see below). It is generally good manners to leave one's cards on the table until the deal is complete.\n\nThe player sitting one seat after the declarer (one with the highest bid and not the dealer) in normal rotation is known as the ''[[eldest hand]]'', also called the ''forehand'' in [[Skat (card game)|Skat]] and other games of German origin. The eldest hand ''leads'' to the first ''trick'', i.e. places the first card of the trick face up in the middle of all players. The other players each follow with a single card, in the direction of play. When every player has played a card to the trick, the trick is evaluated to determine the winner, who takes the cards, places them face down on a pile, and leads to the next trick. The winner or taker of a trick is usually the player who played the highest-value card of the suit that was led, unless the game uses one or more ''[[Trump (card games)|trump]]'' cards (see below).\n\nThe player who leads to a trick is usually allowed to play an arbitrary card from their hand. Some games have restrictions on the first card played in the hand, or may disallow leading a card of a particular [[suit (cards)|suit]] until that suit has been played \"off-suit\" in a prior trick (called \"breaking\" the suit, usually seen in cases of a trump or penalty suit). Other games have special restrictions on the card that must be led to the first trick; usually this is a specific card (e.g., 2{{Clubs}}) and the holder of that card is the eldest hand instead of the person one seat after the dealer.\n\nIn many games, the following players must ''[[#Follow suit|follow suit]]'' if they can, i.e., they must play a card of the same suit if possible. A player who cannot follow suit may ''sluff'' a card, i.e., play a card of a different suit. A trick is won by the player who has played the highest-ranked card of the ''suit led'', i.e., of the suit of the first card in the trick (unless the game uses a [[#Trumps|trump suit]]).\n\nIt can be an advantage to lead to a trick, because the player who leads controls the suit that is led and which others must follow; the leading player playing a suit of which he has many, decreases the chance that anyone else would be able to follow suit; while conversely playing a suit of which he has few, allows him to rid his hand of that suit (known as ''[[Void (cards)|voiding]]'' the suit), freeing him from the restriction to follow suit when that suit is led by another player. On the other hand, it can also be advantageous to be the final player who plays to the trick, because at that point one has full information about the other cards played to the trick; the last player to a trick can play a card just slightly higher or lower than the current winning card, guaranteeing they will win or lose it by the minimum amount necessary, saving more valuable high or low value cards for situations where they must guarantee that a card played early to a trick will win or lose.\n\nWhen all cards have been played, the number or contents of the tricks won by each player is tallied and used to update the score. Scoring based on the play of tricks varies widely between games, but in most games either the number of tricks a player or partnership has won (''plain-trick'' games), or the value of certain cards that the player has won by taking tricks (''point-trick'' games) is important.\n\n== Partnerships ==\n* In many games such as [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]] and [[Oh Hell]], all players play individually against each other.\n* In many four-player games such as [[Contract bridge|Bridge]], [[Euchre]] and [[Spades (card game)|Spades]], the players sitting opposite to each other form a fixed partnership.\n* Some games such as [[Pinochle]] are commonly played with or without partnerships, depending on the number of players.\n* In some contract/auction games for three or more players, e.g. most Tarot variants, the contractor (''declarer'' or ''taker'') plays alone against all opponents, who form an ''ad hoc'' partnership (the ''defenders'').\n* In some games the partnerships are decided by chance \u2013 the contractor forms a partnership with the winner of the first trick, or with the player who holds a certain card. This practice originated from Cinquillo and [[Quadrille (card game)|Quadrille]].\n** In [[K\u00f6nigrufen]] and five-player [[French Tarot]] the taker can call out a suit of which he does not possess the King, and is partnered with whomever does have it against the other three.\n** Standard [[Schafkopf]] is similar: A \"player\" can \"call\" a suit, and the person holding the ace of that suit becomes his partner for the hand. As this is not openly declared, it can be a challenge for the remaining players, to find out who is partnered with whom through cunning playing for several tricks. Aside from that, standard Schafkopf also has several solo options, where the \"player\" plays alone against the rest.\n** In [[Doppelkopf]] the two players holding the black Queens are partners for that hand. Special rules are provided for the case where a single player holds both black Queens.\n\n==Stock==\nIn some games not all cards are distributed to the players, and a ''stock'' remains. This stock can be referred to by different names, depending on the game; ''supply'', ''talon'', ''nest'', ''skat'', ''kitty'', and ''dog'' are common game-specific and/or regional names.\n\nIn some games the stock remains untouched throughout play of the hand; it is simply a pile of \"extra\" cards that will never be played and whose values are unknown, which will reduce the effectiveness of \"[[Card reading (bridge)|counting cards]]\" (a common strategy of keeping track of the cards that have been played or are yet to be played). In games without bidding, trumps may be decided by exposing a card in the stock as in [[Triomphe]]. In other games, the winner of an auction-bidding process (the taker or declarer) may get to exchange cards from his hand with the stock, either by integrating the stock into his hand and then discarding equal cards as in [[Skat (card game)|Skat]], [[Rook (card game)|Rook]] and [[French tarot]], or in a \"blind\" fashion by discarding and drawing as in [[Ombre]]. The stock, either in its original or discarded form, may additionally form part of one or more players' \"scoring piles\" of tricks taken; it may be kept by the declarer, may be won by the player of the first trick, or may go to an opposing player or partnership.\n\nIn some games, especially two-player games, after each trick every player draws a new card. This continues while the stock lasts. Since this drawing mechanism would normally make it difficult or impossible to detect a revoke (for instance, the player may not be able to follow suit, so they play off-suit and then immediately draw a card of the suit led), in the first phase of trick-play (before the stock is empty) players generally need not follow suit. A widespread game of this type is the [[Marriage group]].\n\n== Bidding ==\n\nIn a ''contract'' game the winning and scoring conditions are not fixed but are chosen by one of the players after seeing their hand. In such games, players make ''bids'' depending on the number of tricks or card points they believe they can win during play of the hand. One or more of these bids stands as the ''contract'', and the player who made that bid is rewarded for meeting it or penalized for not meeting it.\n\nIn ''auction'' games, bidding players are competing against each other for the right to attempt to make the contract. In a few games, the contract is fixed (normally a simple majority, less often based on certain cards captured during play) and players' bids are a wager of game points to be won or lost. In others, the bid is a number of tricks or card points the bidder is confident that they or their partnership will take. Either of these can also include the suit to be used as trumps during the hand. Common bids include slam (winning all the tricks), [[mis\u00e8re]] (losing all the tricks), ouvert (the contractor's hand is exposed), playing without using the stock or only part of it, and winning the last trick or other specific tricks. The highest bid becomes the contract and the highest bidder is the ''contractor'', known in some games as the ''declarer'' or ''taker'', who then plays either with or without a partner. The other players become ''opponents'' or ''defenders'', whose main goal is to prevent the contract being met. They may announce a ''contra'' against the contractor which doubles the points for the hand. The contractor can declare a ''recontra'' which will double the points again.\n\nPopular examples of games with auctions include [[Contract bridge]], [[Pinochle]], [[Tarot card games|tarot games]], [[Skat (card game)|Skat]], [[Belote]] and [[Twenty-eight (card game)|Twenty-Eight]]. In many auction games the eldest hand leads to the first trick, regardless of who won the auction, but in some, such as [[Contract bridge|Contract Bridge]], the first lead is made by the player next in rotation after the contractor, so that the contractor plays last to that trick.\n\nIn ''precision'' or ''exact-prediction'' games, all players choose their winning condition independently: to win precisely a predicted number of tricks ([[Oh Hell]]) or card points ([[Jass|Differenzler]]). Each player's bid stands (in partnership games the partners' bids are often combined), and each player or partnership then tries to take exactly the number of tricks or points they bid, and are rewarded or penalized for doing so independently of anyone else's success or failure in meeting their bid. This type of game began to mature in the 20th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Parlett|1990|pages=311\u2013315}}.</ref> Other games generally falling into the exact-prediction category are [[Spades (card game)|Spades]] and [[Ninety-nine (trick-taking card game)|Ninety-Nine]].\n\n==Trumps==\n''[[Trump (card games)|Trump cards]]'' are a set of one or more cards in the deck that, when played, are of higher value than the suit led. If a trick contains any trump cards, it is won by the highest-value trump card played, not the highest-value card of the suit led.\n\nIn most games with trumps, one of the four suits is identified as the ''trump suit''. In the simplest case, there is a static trump suit such as the Spade suit in the game [[Spades (card game)|Spades]], or a dedicated trump suit in the [[Tarot card games|Tarot]] family (in addition to the other four) is featured. More often, a dynamic trump suit is determined by some means, either randomly by selection of a card as in [[Oh Hell]] and the original form of [[Whist]], or decided by the winner or winning bid of an auction as in [[contract bridge]] and some forms of [[Pinochle]]. In certain games, such as Rowboat and Rage, the trump suit may change during the course of the hand, even from trick to trick. Some psychological variety is added to the game and makes it more difficult to cheat if the trump suit is only chosen after dealing.\n\nIn some games, in addition to or separately from a trump suit, certain fixed cards are always the highest trumps, e.g. the Jacks in [[Skat (card game)|Skat]], the Jacks or Jokers in [[Euchre]], and the Rook Bird card in [[Rook (card game)|Rook]]. They are called ''matadors'' after the high trumps in [[Ombre]]. ''Matadors'' either have high point values or special abilities as in [[Spoil Five]] where they can revoke legally.\n\nSome games have more than one trump suit, such as the quasi-trick game [[Stortok]], in which there are two trumps, with one superseding the other. Other games have no trumps; [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]] for instance has no provision for a trump suit of any kind (the Hearts suit for which the game is named has a different significance). Though trump is part of [[contract bridge]], teams can make bids that do not specify a trump suit, and if that is the winning bid then there is no trump suit for that hand (making such a contract is regarded as harder to accomplish).\n\n==Declarations==\nIn some games such as [[Piquet]], [[Tarocchini]], and [[Belote]], before the taking of tricks commences, players can expose certain cards or [[Meld (cards)|melds]] (combinations) that they possess for bonus points. While this phase may seem to award players for pure chance, those who do declare risk letting their opponents develop strategies to counter the cards that they have revealed.\n\n==Follow suit==\nIn many games, ''following suit'' is the obligatory action of playing a card of the same suit as that of the leading suit. A player must follow suit if that player has cards of the leading suit in his hands. There is a large variation of strictness in following suit among games.<ref>McLeod, John. [https://www.pagat.com/mech.html#followsuit Mechanics of Card Games] at [[pagat.com]]. Retrieved 18 February 2017.</ref>\n\nIn most modern games with trump suits, the rules for following suit do not distinguish between the trump suit and the ''plain suits''. If a trick begins with a plain suit card and a later player cannot follow suit, the player may choose freely to either ''slough'' (discard a card of another plain suit), or ''ruff'' (''trump'' the trick by playing a trump card). Subsequent players to the trick must still follow the original suit, and may only discard or trump if they do not hold a card of the suit led. Certain games are \"play to beat\" or \"must-trump\"; if a player cannot follow suit but can play trump, they must play trump, and additionally if they are able they must beat any trump card already played to the trick. [[Pinochle]] and several of the [[Tarot card games]] have this rule.\n\nSome games, notably [[French Tarot]] and a variation of [[Rook (card game)|Rook]], use a special card (in French Tarot's case, the [[The Fool (Tarot card)|Excuse]]) that can be played at any time. If not, he has the choice of playing a trump to possibly win the trick, or rough (waste) a different suit.\n\nIf unable to follow suit or trump, any card can be played. Each trick must contain one card per player, and hence a player unable to satisfy any other instruction is at liberty to play any card. Usually a low-ranking card or one from a short suit is sacrificed. The former is used to protect a higher ranking card while the latter is to help void a suit so as to allow trumping a future trick.\n\nIt is also possible that the specific deal has \"no trump\". In that case, any card other than the leading suit played has no value, in most trick-taking games. In some games such as [[Oh, hell]], where the player may need to not get more tricks to win, playing cards other than the leading suit can be useful.<ref>McLeod, John. [http://www.pagat.com/exact/ohhell.html Oh Hell!] at [[pagat.com]]. Retrieved 18 February 2017.</ref>\n\nFor example, consider the following [[Whist]] hand:\n:: Trump diamonds {{cards|d}}\n* North: {{cards|As|Ks|4h|9d}}\n* East: {{cards|7s|5d|Qc|10c}}\n* South: {{cards|3h|2d|Jd|Ac}}\n* West: {{cards|5s|2s|6h|5c}}\n\nNorth leads the deal with {{spades|K}}. Now, all the other players must follow suit, i.e. play a spade card. East has a spade card, and thus must follow suit by playing {{spades|7}}. South, however, does not have any spade card, and thus is allowed to play any card he wants. If he desires to win the trick, he can override North's {{spades|K}} by playing a diamond card (diamond being the trump), for example {{diamonds|J}}. If he does not want to win the trick, he can slough any other suit, such as {{hearts|3}}. Let us assume that he plays {{diamonds|J}}, overriding North's card. Now, West still has to follow suit, since he has a spade card, and plays {{spades|2}}. South's trump card, gives him an opportunity to escape following suit, and he wins the trick.\n\nIf a player who can follow suit does not do so, or in games with additional restrictions on card play, not following these restrictions is known as a [[revoke]], or 'renege'. A revoke typically cannot be discovered at the time when it is committed, but when a player plays off-suit to a trick, competent opponents will make a mental note that the player does not hold the suit led, and will notice later if the player later plays a card of the suit they were thought to be void in. The situation is similar for other types of revoke. Most game rules prescribe a severe penalty for a revoke and may also result in the hand being voided (a \"misdeal\"). Decks of cards have been marketed for trick-taking games with the traditional French suit symbols, but in four colors; these are often called [[Four-color deck|\"no-revoke\" decks]], as the color contrast between each suit makes a potential revoking play easier to spot and harder to do accidentally.\n\nIn some trick games\u2014typically ones in which players are not penalized for winning tricks, and there is no requirement for trumping or following suit when possible\u2014players may ''slough'', or play a card face down.  A card so played is incapable of winning the trick; but sloughing has the advantage that the other players cannot see what card is played. As this form of sloughing has the potential to be used to cheat in most games (i.e. playing a winning card face-down to avoid taking an \"overtrick\" or a trick containing penalty points) and is thus not allowed, ''sloughing'' in the vernacular more often refers to simply discarding an off-suit card on a trick, particularly one that could be dangerous to that player if kept. This form of sloughing is important in evasion games and in some contract games where \"overtricks\" are penalized; in [[Oh Hell]], for instance, a player who cannot follow suit may elect to discard a card that would win if played to follow suit later, thus reducing the chance that the player will \"bag\", or take more tricks than needed. This is common in [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]], where high-value cards (especially Spades and Hearts) are dangerous as they increase the chance of winning a trick with penalty points.\n\nSome games such as [[Pinochle]] use several decks shuffled together. In these games, there may be several equal winning cards in a trick; such games then use other rules to break ties. Common rules include:\n* the first-played of the tying cards wins\n* the last-played of the tying cards wins\n* The tying cards cancel each other out, and the trick is taken by the next-highest card that was played.\n* The tying cards cancel each other out, but the trick is spoiled (ignored).\n\nA common additional rule to reduce these occurrences is that a player cannot play a card tying the current high card unless they would renege or fail to overtrump by making any other play.\n\n==Scoring==\nWhen all tricks have been played, the winner of the hand and the players' scores can be determined. The determining factor in plain-trick games (the most popular form of trick-taking games in English-speaking countries) is simply how many tricks each player or partnership has taken. In point-trick games, certain card values are worth varying points, and the players sum the points from cards in their \"scoring piles\" that were accumulated by taking tricks. Points for cards, and the method of counting points, vary by game; in Rook, for example, the 5-card of each color is worth 5 points, the 10 and 14 (or Ace) is worth 10, and the Rook Bird (or Joker) is worth 20, while all other cards are worth nothing. Many Chinese card games like Finding Friends use a very similar system, in which each 5-card is worth 5 points, and the 10 and King are each worth 10 points.<ref>Rules for Chinese trick-taking card game [http://www.zhao-pengyou.com/ \"Finding Friends (Zhao Pengyou)\"]. Retrieved on 7 September 2018.</ref> Pinochle has many popular scoring variants usually based on point values for face cards and Aces, while pip cards score no points. In French Tarot, all cards have a value including a half-point, and are traditionally scored in pairs of a high-value and a low-value card which results in a whole-point value for the pair.\n\nIn the most common ''positive'' or ''race'' games, players seek to win as many tricks or card points as possible. To win a hand, a player typically needs to win a minimal number of tricks or card points; this minimal threshold is usually called the \"contract\", and may be defined by the game's rules (a simple majority of total available points or tricks, or tiered thresholds depending on which player or side has captured certain cards), or the result of an \"auction\" or \"bidding\" process. A player who wins more than the number of tricks or card points necessary for winning the hand may be rewarded with a higher score, or conversely (in exact-prediction games) they may be penalized.\n\nThere are also ''negative'' or ''evasion'' games, in which the object is to avoid tricks or card points. E.g. in Hearts each card point won in a trick contributes negatively to the score. A special type is ''mis\u00e8re'' games, which are usually variants of positive games which can only be won by not winning a single trick.\n\nOther criteria also occur. Sometimes the last trick has special significance. In ''marriage games'' such as Pinochle the winner of the last trick receives 10 points in addition to the card points, while in ''final-trick'' games such as [[c\u1eaft t\u00ea]] only the winner of the last trick can win a hand. There are also blends between positive and negative games, e.g. the aim may be to win a certain prescribed number of tricks. Many card games, regardless of their normal scoring mechanism, give bonuses to players or partnerships who win all tricks or possible points in a hand, or conversely lose all tricks or points.\n\nGames usually end after every player has had an equal chance to be the dealer. The number of rotations varies widely among games. Some games have a cumulative score where all points from each hand add up. Others assign only a set number of game points for winning a hand. For example, a player or side that wins one hand may be awarded one game point, two if they achieve a slam. The player or side with the most game points or the first to reach a certain number of card or game points, is considered the winner.\n\n==Special variations==\n=== Variations to basic rules ===\nNumerous further variations to the basic rules may occur, and only a few examples can be mentioned here:\n* Certain games require the holder of a certain card value to play it as the lead to the first trick of a hand; [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]], as commonly played in North America, requires the player holding the 2{{Clubs}} to play it as the lead-off card. Variants of [[Pinochle]] sometimes require the first player to the left of the dealer that holds a ''dix'' (9{{Clubs}}) to lead off.\n* There may be restrictions on leading certain suits; a common Hearts rule is that a player may not lead a Heart until at least one trick has had a Heart played off-suit to another trick. Spades has a similar but less-common variation regarding its trump suit.\n* There are trick-taking games played with [[Domino]] tiles instead of playing cards. These include the Chinese [[Tien Gow]] and [[42 (dominoes)|Texas 42]]. [[Giog]] is played with [[Xiangqi|Chinese chess]] tiles.\n* Many games are played with one or more ''[[stripped deck]]s'' (a deck from which certain card values are removed). The most common stripped deck is a [[piquet deck]], used for [[piquet]], [[Belote]], [[Skat (card game)|Skat]], [[Euchre]], [[Bezique]] and (with two piquet decks) [[Pinochle]], among others. [[Rook (card game)|Rook]]'s main variant, Kentucky Discard, uses the equivalent of a 52-card deck with all card values 2\u20134 removed. Most regional [[Tarot]] variants, especially Central European and Italian variants like Tarock and Tarocco, use some subset of the \"full\" 78-card Tarot deck.\n* In Bridge the partner of the contractor or ''declarer'' is called ''dummy'' and does not actively participate in the play; dummy's hand is instead laid on the table face-up after the opening lead, and declarer chooses the cards from dummy's hand to play during dummy's turns.\n* In [[Karuta#Unsun Karuta|Hachinin-meri]] and Truf, trumps are played face down. When the trick is finished, the trumps are revealed to see who won the trick.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Depaulis|first1=Thierry|title=Unsun, a Far-eastern Cousin of Ombre|journal=[[The Playing-Card]]|date=1983|volume=12|issue=1|pages=39\u201344}}</ref><ref>McLeod, John. [http://www.pagat.com/exact/truf.html Truf] at [[pagat.com]]. Retrieved 25 January 2016.</ref>\n* In many trumpless games that do not require following suit, sluffing is done face down. This is done in [[Madiao]], [[Tien Gow]], [[Tam c\u00fac]], [[:zh:\u516d\u864e\u724c|Six Tigers]], [[Ganjifa]], [[Kaiserspiel]], and Brazilian [[Truco]].\n* Some cards lose their trick-taking power if they are not led or played in a specific trick as in [[Karn\u00f6ffel]], [[Tien Gow]], and [[Ganjifa]].\n* In [[tarot game]]s played outside of Central Europe, [[The Fool (Tarot card)|the Fool]] is a special card that excuses the player from following suit. Except in rare circumstances in some games, it can neither capture nor be captured. Usually a non-counting card is given as compensation to the trick's winner by the Fool's owner.\n\n=== Rules in Austrian and German games ===\nIn games derived from Austria and Germany, trick-taking is governed by the rules called ''Zw\u00e4nge''. The three main ones are ''Farbzwang'', ''Stichzwang'' and ''Trumpfzwang''. Although they broadly equate to rules in English-speaking countries, there are no single-word equivalents. For many games of this type, applying these rules correctly is crucial to the type of contract being played.\n\n==== ''Farbzwang'' ====\n''Farbzwang'' (or ''Bedienzwang'') literally means \"suit compulsion\" and is the rule that players must follow the suit of the first card to be led to the trick, provided that they have a card of that suit. If a player does not have a card of the led suit, they may play ('discard') a card of their choice. If a player has several cards of the led suit, they may choose which to play. In most cases it makes sense to play a higher ranking card.\n\n==== ''Stichzwang'' ====\n''Stichzwang'' means \"trick compulsion\" and is the rule that players must attempt to win the trick if they are able, either by playing a higher card of the led suit or by playing a trump card.\n\n==== ''Farbzwang'' with ''Stichzwang'' ====\nSome games apply ''Farbzwang'' and ''Stichzwang'' together, which means that a player, when it is his turn, must:\n* take the trick with a higher card of the led suit. If unable to do so, he must\n* discard a lower card of the led suit. If that is not possible, he must\n* take the trick with a trump card, but if that is also not feasible, he may\n* discard a card of his choice.\n\n''Farbzwang'', the requirement to follow suit, always takes precedence over ''Stichzwang''. A player is not allowed to take the trick with a trump if he can follow suit.\n\n==== ''Trumpfzwang'' ====\n''Trumpzwang'' means \"trump compulsion\" and requires that a player ''must'' play a trump if he cannot follow suit. In other words, he may not simply discard, if he cannot follow suit.\n\n''Example'': Acorns are trumps. Forehand plays the 8 of Bells, middlehand trumps with a 10 of Acorns; rearhand has no Bells, but does have a trump card, the 8 of Acorns. He must play this and cannot discard another non-trump card in order to keep the trump for a subsequent trick.\n\n==== ''Tarockzwang'' ====\n''Tarockzwang'' is used in [[tarock game]]s such as [[K\u00f6nigrufen]] and [[Tapp-Tarock]] and means \"Tarock compulsion\" or the requirement to play a Tarock card if one is led to the trick or if a player is unable to follow suit. It is a form of ''Trumpfzwang''.\n\n== Examples ==\n{{Related article|List of Ace-Ten games}}\nTrick-taking games may be divided into point-trick games and plain-trick games. Examples of each are as follows:\n\n=== Point-trick games ===\nPoint-trick game are those in which win or loss is determined by the total value of the \"counters\" in the tricks.<ref name=\"parlett,2008,644\u2013645\">{{harvnb|Parlett|2008|pages=644\u2013645}}.</ref> The counters are cards with a point value, sometimes referred to as \"card points\" to avoid confusion with \"game points\" awarded for winning the game and/or bonuses.\n\nExamples include:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20}}\n* [[Bavarian Tarock]]\n* [[Belote]]\n* [[B\u00e9zique]]\n* [[Binokel]]\n* [[Doppelkopf]]\n* [[Jass]]\n* Finding Friends ([[Zhao Pengyou]])\n* [[Schafkopf]]\n* [[Schnapsen]] or [[Sixty-six (card game)|Sixty-six]]\n* [[Skat (card game)|Skat]]\n* [[Tarock]] games ([[French Tarot]], [[K\u00f6nigrufen]], [[Zwanzigerrufen]], etc.)\n* [[Trappola]] (Bulka)\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n=== Plain-trick games ===\nPlain-trick games are those in which the outcome is determined by the number of tricks taken, regardless of their content.<ref name=\"parlett,2008,644\u2013645\"/>\n\nExamples of plain-trick games include:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20}}\n* [[Boston (card game)|Boston]]\n* [[Bridge (card game)|Bridge]]\n* [[\u00c9cart\u00e9]]\n* [[Jabberwocky (card game)|Jabberwocky]]\n* [[Ombre]] and [[Quadrille (card game)|Quadrille]]\n* [[Piquet]]\n* [[Pr\u00e9f\u00e9rence]]\n* [[Solo Whist]]\n* [[Tippen]]\n* [[Watten (card game)|Watten]]\n* [[Whist]]\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\nIn games that consist of several successive, different, trick-taking contracts, such as Herzeln or Quodlibet, it is not possible to categorise them as either point- or plain-trick games.\n\n=== Trick-avoidance games ===\nTrick-avoidance games are those in which the aim is to avoid taking certain tricks or to avoid taking all tricks. [[Misere]] or [[Bettel (cards)|bettel]] are contracts in which the declarer undertakes to win no tricks. There are also contracts like [[Piccolo (cards)|Piccolo]] in which the aim is to take only one trick. Examples include:\n\n* [[Bassadewitz]]\n* [[Grasobern]]\n* [[Hearts (card game)|Hearts]]\n* [[Polignac (card game)|Polignac]]\n* [[Slobberhannes]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of trick-taking games]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Citation\n|last1=Dummett\n|first1=Michael\n|last2=Mann\n|first2=Sylvia\n|title=The Game of Tarot: From Ferrara to Salt Lake City\n|year=1980\n|publisher=Duckworth\n|isbn=9780715610145}}\n* {{Citation\n|last1=Kastner\n|first1=Hugo\n|last2=Folkvord\n|first2=Gerald K.\n|title=Die gro\u00dfe Humboldt Enzyklop\u00e4die der Kartenspiele\n|year=2005\n|publisher=Humboldt\n|language=German\n|isbn=978-3-89994-058-9}}\n* {{Citation\n|editor-last=McLeod\n|editor-first=John\n|title=Card Games website\n|url=http://www.pagat.com/}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Parlett\n|first=David\n|title=The Oxford guide to card games: a historical survey\n|year=1990\n|publisher=Oxford University Press\n|isbn=978-0-19-214165-1\n|url-access=registration\n|url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordguidetocar00parl\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Parlett\n|first=David\n|title=The Penguin Book of Card Games\n|year=2008\n|edition=3rd\n|publisher=Penguin Books\n|isbn=978-0-14-103787-5}}.\n\n{{List of trick-taking games}}\n{{Tarot and Tarock card games}}\n\n[[Category:Card game terminology]]\n[[Category:Trick-taking games| ]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromFrench TarottoFrench tarotusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trick-taking_game"}
{"title_page": "Alejandro Agag", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=December 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2018}}\n{{Spanish name|Agag|Longo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Alejandro Agag\n|image         = AGAG-MONACO-2009-(10).jpg\n|image_size    = 200px\n|caption       =\n|birth_name    = Alejandro Tarik Agag Longo\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1970|9|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Madrid]], Spain\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|nationality   = Spanish\n|other_names   =\n|known_for     = Spanish businessman and former [[politician]]. His present interests lie in the fields of finance, advertising and sports\n|occupation    = Chairman of Addax Capital LLP; Owner of [[Barwa Addax]] [[GP2 Series]] Team; former Chairman of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.]]\n|title         =\n|party         = [[People's Party (Spain)|Partido Popular]] ([[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]])\n|religion      =\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Ana Aznar Botella|5 September 2002}}\n|partner       =\n|parents       =\n|website       =\n}}\n'''Alejandro Tarik Agag Longo''' (born 18 September 1970, in [[Madrid]]) is a Spanish businessman and former [[politician]], based in [[London]] as the Chairman of Addax Capital LLP.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn to an [[Algeria]]n-[[Belgium|Belgian]] father Youssef Agag, who was a banker, and a Spanish mother, Soledad Longo \u00c1lvarez de Soto Mayor,<ref>{{cite news| title =Who\u2019s who: Of bankers, builders and fortune makers| publisher =ft.com| url =http://www.ft.com/cms/fb91d0da-7726-11dc-9de8-0000779fd2ac,dwp_uuid=a5f83b7e-8120-11dc-9f14-0000779fd2ac.html}}</ref> Agag enjoyed an international upbringing in Madrid, including primary and secondary schooling at the Colegio Retamar, Pozuelo de Alarc\u00f3n, a fee-paying school belonging to the [[Opus Dei]], an ultra-conservative Catholic movement, [[Paris]] and [[New York City|New York]]. Agag graduated with a degree in Economics and Business studies from the Colegio Universitario de Estudios Financieros (CUNEF) in [[Madrid]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.multivu.com/players/English/63309-qualcomm-and-fia-formula-e-championship/flexSwf/impAsset/document/ee32c7df-ae7c-4039-bdd3-7fa51ed3799e.pdf|title = BIOGRAPHY \u2013 ALEJANDRO AGAG CEO, FORMULA E HOLDINGS|date = |accessdate = |website = MultiVu|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> a private entity financed by the Spanish banks, and is fluent in four languages, Spanish, English, French and Italian.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Political career==\nAgag's political career began when, at the early age of 18, he became a member of [[Nuevas Generaciones]] (NNGG), the youth organization of the main center-right Spanish party [[People's Party (Spain)|Partido Popular]], which at the time was in the opposition. Having been actively involved in politics while at University, he quickly moved up the ranks of the youth structure of the party, joining, due to his knowledge of languages, the international relations department.<ref>{{cite news| title =Parliamentary Questions| publisher =europarl.europa.eu| url =http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sidesSearch/search.do?type=QP&term=5&author=4315&language=EN&startValue=10}}</ref>\n\nDuring that time Agag travelled extensively representing NNGG in organizations such as [[DEMYC]] and [[EYCD]], center-right parties from Europe and the world that brought together youth political branches. Agag was elected International Secretary of NNGG at their congress in 1994.\n\nIn the same year, Agag graduated in economics and was offered the position of Deputy Secretary General of the [[European People's Party]]. An offer that was as a direct result of the election \u2013 a few months earlier \u2013 of the German [[Klaus Welle]] as Secretary General. Welle and Agag met in the youth organizations level, and Welle took Agag with him to the EPP \u2013 Agag was 23 at the time. That year, Agag also ran for a seat in the [[European Parliament]], he campaigned in towns and villages in [[Extremadura]]; he was not elected at this time.\n\nAs deputy secretary general, Agag was in charge of coordinating the different policy working groups within the EPP, and drafting of policy papers to be presented at the congress. As DSG Agag was a member of the EPP Summit, which meets before the European Council meetings and includes all of EPP's Heads of State and Government.<ref>{{cite news| title =Ppe, ultimatum a chi sta con la sinistra| publisher =archiviostorico.corriere.it| url =http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2000/settembre/04/Ppe_ultimatum_chi_sta_con_co_0_0009045691.shtml| date =4 September 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Silvio, Pierferdinando, Flavio Tutti gli amici italiani di Agag| publisher =archiviostorico.corriere.it| url =http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2005/agosto/09/Silvio_Pierferdinando_Flavio_Tutti_gli_co_9_050809043.shtml| date =9 August 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996 the Center-right won the elections in Spain, and Agag was offered the position to become designated aid of the President of the Government, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aznar]]. The President had three aides, one diplomat, one military and one political (Agag). He was 25 at the time, and spent three years in that position.\n\nIn 1999, at 28 years of age, he was elected a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for the [[People's Party (Spain)|Partido Popular]].<ref name=europarl-agag>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/4315/ALEJANDRO_AGAG+LONGO_home.html |title=Alejandro AGAG LONGO |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> He entered the Economic and Monetary affairs commission, focusing in antitrust policy.<ref name=europarl-agag/><ref name=addax-aboutus>{{cite web |url=http://www.addaxcapital.com/en/services/addax-about-us.html |title=About Us |publisher=ADDAX |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115213649/http://www.addaxcapital.com/en/services/addax-about-us.html |archivedate=15 November 2010}}</ref> In 2000 he led the Parliaments report on antitrust policy, and was active in redrafting the present antitrust rules.\n\n[[File:Flickr - europeanpeoplesparty - EPP Congress Berlin 2001 (1).jpg|thumb|left|Agag and [[Wilfried Martens]] at the [[European People's Party]] congress in [[Berlin]]]] \nEarlier that year he had also been elected [[Secretary General]] of the European People's Party,<ref>{{cite news| title =Group of the European People's Party (Christian Democrats) and European Democrats| publisher =europarl.europa.eu| url =http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/archive/alphaOrder/view.do?language=EN&id=4315}}</ref> replacing his colleague Klaus Welle. During his mandate as SG the organization expanded to the east of Europe, during that period it incorporated more than 20 new political parties from the region. Later that year, for the first time, the EPP won the European Parliament elections and became the largest political force in Europe.<ref>{{cite news| title =Blair's rapport with Berlusconi upsets his old friends on the left| publisher =independent.co.uk| url =https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/blairs-rapport-with-berlusconi-upsets-his-old-friends-on-the-left-674231.html| date =16 June 2001}}</ref>\n\nAgag was active in the Italian political life. For example Agag intervened in the closing campaign rally of Forza Italia in [[Rome]].\n\nIn 2000 Agag was elected in [[Mexico]] Secretary General of the Christian Democratic International, renamed at that meeting [[Centrist Democrat International|Centrist Democratic International]]. This global political organization has over 90 member parties from all over the world.\n\nAgag remained a member of the European Parliament until 2002.<ref name=europarl-agag/>\n\n==Business career==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=October 2019}}\nIn 2002 Agag moved to London and started his own consultancy firm. He has been very active in multiple fields, including telecoms, energy, and especially media. Agag expanded his activities to financial advisory and fund management, forming a company called Addax Capital LLP, which is regulated by the FSA. Agag is currently Chairman of Addax and was joined in 2009 by [[Ignacio Mu\u00f1oz Alonso]], former CEO of [[N M Rothschild & Sons|Rothschild Bank]] in Spain, who worked for [[Lehman Brothers]] before that.\n\nIn 2007, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' named him as one of the 10 \"shakers and movers\" of the Spanish economy, and he was described as a \"political hopeful, economist, banker and indefatigable dealmaker\".\n\nAgag is frequently mentioned in the media for his extensive range of contacts, both political and business, from all over the world. The Spanish newspaper \u2018[[El Pa\u00eds|El Pais]]\u2019 once described his Nokia [[SIM card|SIM Card]] as \"Priceless\".\n\nIn 2008, [[GQ|GQ Magazine]] elected him as the Spanish \"Businessman of the Year.\"\n\n==Sports : Formula 1, Formula E, GP2 and football==\nAgag business activity within sports mainly focuses on motorsport and football. According to the Spanish newspaper \u2018El Pais\u2019, Agag, together with [[Flavio Briatore]], acquired very early on the [[Formula One]] T.V. rights for Spain. This was achieved via a U.K. based company and played a key role in the huge expansion of Formula One in Spain where television audiences have multiplied over the past few years. Agag is also very heavily involved in the \u2018sponsorship\u2019 side of the business, he is said to be behind some of the major deals lately achieved in the sport.<ref>{{cite news| title =El conseguidor| publisher =elpais.com| url =http://www.elpais.com/articulo/reportajes/conseguidor/elpepusocdmg/20070225elpdmgrep_1/Tes| date =25 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Agag, da Aznar alla Formula 1 una nuova vita tra sport e affari| publisher =archiviostorico.corriere.it| url =http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2005/agosto/12/Agag_Aznar_alla_Formula_una_co_8_050812004.shtml| date =12 August 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Who is Alejandro Agag and why does it matter?| publisher =grandprix.com| url =http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19564.html| date =29 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nAgag owns the [[Barwa Addax]] [[GP2 Series]] Team which won the title in 2008 and was runner-up in 2009.<ref>{{cite news| title =Alejandro Agag sabe por d\u00f3nde sopla el viento de la F\u00f3rmula 1| publisher =elconfidencial.com| url =http://www.elconfidencial.com/dentro-del-paddock/alejandro-agag-formula-uno-20100608.html| date =8 June 2010}}</ref> He took over the Team from former F1 driver, [[Adri\u00e1n Campos]], in mid-2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Renamed Addax team sign Grosjean |publisher=autosport.com |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/73447 |date=26 February 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-26 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mqhLkijp?url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/73447 |archivedate=17 January 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The team's main sponsor is the Qatari real estate company, Barwa. Three drivers from Addax, [[Romain Grosjean]], [[Vitaly Petrov]] and [[Lucas di Grassi]], have made it to the F1.<ref>{{cite news| title =Addax Team sees Perez move to F1| publisher =motorsport.com| url =http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=390162&FS=GP2| archive-url =https://archive.is/20120907012445/http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=390162&FS=GP2| url-status =dead| archive-date =7 September 2012| date =6 October 2010}}</ref> In 2010, Agag started competing in GP3 with the Addax GP3 Team.<ref>{{cite news|title=ADDAX TEAM SIGN MEXICAN DRIVER PABLO SANCHEZ FOR GP3 2010 SEASON |publisher=theleader.info |url=http://www.theleader.info/article/21746/spain/national/addax-team-sign-mexican-driver-pablo-sanchez-for-gp3-2010-season/ |date=12 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325064638/http://www.theleader.info/article/21746/spain/national/addax-team-sign-mexican-driver-pablo-sanchez-for-gp3-2010-season/ |archivedate=25 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Alejandro Agag: Basta politica, ora solo corse| publisher =rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it| url =http://rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it/rotta_a_sud_ovest/2010/05/alejandro-agag-basta-politica-ora-solo-corse.html}} {{dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Barwa Campos Team begin season with victory |publisher=gulf-times.com |url=http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=290581&version=1&template_id=49&parent_id=29 |date=14 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515121625/http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=290581&version=1&template_id=49&parent_id=29 |archivedate=15 May 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThrough his connection within sport, Agag has formed friendships with [[Flavio Briatore]], [[Bernie Ecclestone]] and [[Lakshmi Mittal]].<ref>{{cite news| title =Alejandro Agag es ya uno de los grandes empresarios de la F\u00f3rmula 1 de la mano de Flavio Briatore| publisher =elmundo.es| url =http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2005/08/11/espana/1123720238.html| date =11 August 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Alejandro Agag says no to Bernie Ecclestone| publisher =duemotori.com| url =http://www.duemotori.com/news/f1/24255_Alejandro_Agag_says_no_to_Bernie_Ecclestone.php| date =28 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alejandro Agag, dopo Bernie Ecclestone? |publisher=rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it |url=http://rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it/rotta_a_sud_ovest/2007/02/alejandro_agag_.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510130320/http://rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it/rotta_a_sud_ovest/2007/02/alejandro_agag_.html |archivedate=10 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alejandro Agag: \"He visto a muchos ricos arruinarse con la F1\" |publisher=intereconomia.com |url=http://www.intereconomia.com/noticias/alejandro-agag-%E2%80%9Che-visto-muchos-ricos-arruinarse-f1%E2%80%9D |date=8 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717185620/http://www.intereconomia.com/noticias/alejandro-agag-%E2%80%9Che-visto-muchos-ricos-arruinarse-f1%E2%80%9D |archivedate=17 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Together, they bought the English football club [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=QPR football club recommends 1p/shr offer from Flavio Briatore's Sarita Capital |publisher=abcmoney.co.uk |url=http://www.abcmoney.co.uk/news/032007127826.htm |date=3 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100416070915/http://www.abcmoney.co.uk/news/032007127826.htm |archivedate=16 April 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAgag served as chairman of QPR for a few months during the take-over then remained in the Club as a shareholder. The plan was to have QPR promoted to the English Premier League, a feat that was achieved in 2011.<ref>{{cite news| title =QPR tycoons hesitate on spending spree | publisher =telegraph.co.uk| url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2288449/QPR-tycoons-hesitate-on-spending-spree.html| date =10 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/may/07/qpr-leeds-united-championship | title=Joy and relief for QPR after FA clear the path to promotion  | date=7 May 2011 | first=John | last=Ashdown | newspaper=The Guardian | accessdate=12 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHe is currently in charge of the [[FIA Formula E Championship|Formula E Championship]], an electric car racing series. The [[2014\u201315 Formula E season|inaugural season]] began on September 2014 and lasted until June 2015. Formula E Holdings, whose CEO is Alejandro Agag, has set up races in ten different cities around the world which are [[Beijing ePrix|Beijing]], [[Putrajaya ePrix|Putrajaya]], [[Punta del Este ePrix|Punta del Este]], [[Buenos Aires ePrix|Buenos Aires]], [[Miami ePrix|Miami]], [[Long Beach ePrix|Long Beach]], [[Monaco ePrix|Monaco]], [[Berlin ePrix|Berlin]], [[Moscow ePrix|Moscow]] and [[London ePrix|London]].<ref name=cities>[http://www.fiaformulae.com/en/calendar.aspx \u00abFormula E's calendar\u00bb] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228002842/http://www.fiaformulae.com/en/calendar.aspx |date=28 December 2014 }}. date =12 August 2014.</ref> The races take place in [[street circuit]]s and began in Beijing on 13 September 2014.<ref name=Beijing>[http://www.formulaegreen.com/2014/05/19/calendario-del-campeonato-de-formula-e-2014-2015-estas-preparado/ \u00abFormula E's beginning\u00bb] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140812102008/http://www.formulaegreen.com/2014/05/19/calendario-del-campeonato-de-formula-e-2014-2015-estas-preparado/ |date=12 August 2014 }}. date =12 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 5 September 2002, Agag married Ana Aznar Botella, the daughter of then Prime Minister [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aznar]] and politician [[Ana Botella]], at [[El Escorial]] in Madrid. Guests included King [[Juan Carlos I]] and Queen [[Sofia of Spain]]. British Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] and Italian Prime Minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]] served as witnesses.<ref name=euobserver-20020907>{{cite news |url=https://euobserver.com/political/7474 |title=Spanish wedding turned into a political affair |last=Spinant |first=Daniela |website=EUobserver |date=7 September 2002 |accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=bbc-20020905>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/2239721.stm |title=In pictures: Aznar's daughter marries |work=BBC News |date=5 September 2002 |accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite conference | author = Alejandro Agag | author2 = Group of the European People's Party (Christian Democrats) and European Democrats in the EU Parliament. | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=DRC3xZlEMcYC&pg=PA3 | title = The future of the European people's party | conference = Our vision of Europe : proximity, competitiveness and visibility. | via = [http://archive.is/4pCuE/ archive.is] | isbn = 9789044111804 | location = Leuvent | publisher = Garant | year = 2001 | pages = 239\u2013242 | oclc = 912254670}}<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=OEZ-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236 | title = international bibliography for the political science | page = 236 | chapter = Bibliography for 2002 | author = British Library of Political and Economic Science - Routledge | publisher = Routledge | volume = 51 | date = March 10, 2004 | isbn = 9781134339969 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190830165307/https://books.google.it/books?id=OEZ-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236&dq=%22Our+vision+of+Europe+:+proximity,+competitiveness+and+visibility.%22&source=bl&ots=tDAP53H2Qb&sig=ACfU3U2RJcCN0QZSGMpm1VzyrxrLOpysWQ&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjq89WWh6vkAhVLiqQKHSZ2AdY4ChDoATAAegQICRAB%23v=onepage&q=%22Our%20vision%20of%20Europe%20:%20proximity,%20competitiveness%20and%20visibility.%22&f=false | archive-date = 30 August 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 30 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{commons category|Alejandro Agag}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agag, Alejandro}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Madrid]]\n[[Category:People's Party (Spain) politicians]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Algerian descent]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Auto racing executives]]\n[[Category:Formula E people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advert|date=December 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2018}}\n{{Spanish name|Agag|Longo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Alejandro Agag\n|image         = AGAG-MONACO-2009-(10).jpg\n|image_size    = 200px\n|caption       =\n|birth_name    = Alejandro Tarik Agag Longo\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1970|9|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Madrid]], Spain\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|nationality   = Spanish\n|other_names   =\n|known_for     = Spanish businessman and former [[politician]]. His present interests lie in the fields of finance, advertising and sports\n|occupation    = Chairman of Addax Capital LLP; Owner of [[Barwa Addax]] [[GP2 Series]] Team; former Chairman of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.]]\n|title         =\n|party         = [[People's Party (Spain)|Partido Popular]] ([[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]])\n|religion      =\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Ana Aznar Botella|5 September 2002}}\n|partner       =\n|parents       =\n|website       =\n}}\n'''Alejandro Tarik Agag Longo''' (born 18 September 1970, in [[Madrid]]) is a Spanish businessman and former [[politician]], based in [[London]] as the Chairman of Addax Capital LLP.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn to an [[Algeria]]n-[[Belgium|Belgian]] father Youssef Agag, who was a banker, and a Spanish mother, Soledad Longo \u00c1lvarez de Soto Mayor,<ref>{{cite news| title =Who\u2019s who: Of bankers, builders and fortune makers| publisher =ft.com| url =http://www.ft.com/cms/fb91d0da-7726-11dc-9de8-0000779fd2ac,dwp_uuid=a5f83b7e-8120-11dc-9f14-0000779fd2ac.html}}</ref> Agag enjoyed an international upbringing in Madrid, including primary and secondary schooling at the Colegio Retamar, Pozuelo de Alarc\u00f3n, a fee-paying school belonging to the [[Opus Dei]], an ultra-conservative Catholic movement, [[Paris]] and [[New York City|New York]]. Agag graduated with a degree in Economics and Business studies from the Colegio Universitario de Estudios Financieros (CUNEF) in [[Madrid]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.multivu.com/players/English/63309-qualcomm-and-fia-formula-e-championship/flexSwf/impAsset/document/ee32c7df-ae7c-4039-bdd3-7fa51ed3799e.pdf|title = BIOGRAPHY \u2013 ALEJANDRO AGAG CEO, FORMULA E HOLDINGS|date = |accessdate = |website = MultiVu|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> a private entity financed by the Spanish banks, and is fluent in four languages, Spanish, English, French and Italian.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Political career==\nAgag's political career began when, at the early age of 18, he became a member of [[Nuevas Generaciones]] (NNGG), the youth organization of the main center-right Spanish party [[People's Party (Spain)|Partido Popular]], which at the time was in the opposition. Having been actively involved in politics while at University, he quickly moved up the ranks of the youth structure of the party, joining, due to his knowledge of languages, the international relations department.<ref>{{cite news| title =Parliamentary Questions| publisher =europarl.europa.eu| url =http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sidesSearch/search.do?type=QP&term=5&author=4315&language=EN&startValue=10}}</ref>\n\nDuring that time Agag travelled extensively representing NNGG in organizations such as [[DEMYC]] and [[EYCD]], center-right parties from Europe and the world that brought together youth political branches. Agag was elected International Secretary of NNGG at their congress in 1994.\n\nIn the same year, Agag graduated in economics and was offered the position of Deputy Secretary General of the [[European People's Party]]. An offer that was as a direct result of the election \u2013 a few months earlier \u2013 of the German [[Klaus Welle]] as Secretary General. Welle and Agag met in the youth organizations level, and Welle took Agag with him to the EPP \u2013 Agag was 23 at the time. That year, Agag also ran for a seat in the [[European Parliament]], he campaigned in towns and villages in [[Extremadura]]; he was not elected at this time.\n\nAs deputy secretary general, Agag was in charge of coordinating the different policy working groups within the EPP, and drafting of policy papers to be presented at the congress. As DSG Agag was a member of the EPP Summit, which meets before the European Council meetings and includes all of EPP's Heads of State and Government.<ref>{{cite news| title =Ppe, ultimatum a chi sta con la sinistra| publisher =archiviostorico.corriere.it| url =http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2000/settembre/04/Ppe_ultimatum_chi_sta_con_co_0_0009045691.shtml| date =4 September 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Silvio, Pierferdinando, Flavio Tutti gli amici italiani di Agag| publisher =archiviostorico.corriere.it| url =http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2005/agosto/09/Silvio_Pierferdinando_Flavio_Tutti_gli_co_9_050809043.shtml| date =9 August 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996 the Center-right won the elections in Spain, and Agag was offered the position to become designated aid of the President of the Government, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aznar]]. The President had three aides, one diplomat, one military and one political (Agag). He was 25 at the time, and spent three years in that position.\n\nIn 1999, at 28 years of age, he was elected a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for the [[People's Party (Spain)|Partido Popular]].<ref name=europarl-agag>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/4315/ALEJANDRO_AGAG+LONGO_home.html |title=Alejandro AGAG LONGO |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> He entered the Economic and Monetary affairs commission, focusing in antitrust policy.<ref name=europarl-agag/><ref name=addax-aboutus>{{cite web |url=http://www.addaxcapital.com/en/services/addax-about-us.html |title=About Us |publisher=ADDAX |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115213649/http://www.addaxcapital.com/en/services/addax-about-us.html |archivedate=15 November 2010}}</ref> In 2000 he led the Parliaments report on antitrust policy, and was active in redrafting the present antitrust rules.\n\n[[File:Flickr - europeanpeoplesparty - EPP Congress Berlin 2001 (1).jpg|thumb|left|Agag and [[Wilfried Martens]] at the [[European People's Party]] congress in [[Berlin]]]] \nEarlier that year he had also been elected [[Secretary General]] of the European People's Party,<ref>{{cite news| title =Group of the European People's Party (Christian Democrats) and European Democrats| publisher =europarl.europa.eu| url =http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/archive/alphaOrder/view.do?language=EN&id=4315}}</ref> replacing his colleague Klaus Welle. During his mandate as SG the organization expanded to the east of Europe, during that period it incorporated more than 20 new political parties from the region. Later that year, for the first time, the EPP won the European Parliament elections and became the largest political force in Europe.<ref>{{cite news| title =Blair's rapport with Berlusconi upsets his old friends on the left| publisher =independent.co.uk| url =https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/blairs-rapport-with-berlusconi-upsets-his-old-friends-on-the-left-674231.html| date =16 June 2001}}</ref>\n\nAgag was also very active in [[Italy]]. Making a controversial decision, and against some member parties within the organization, he pushed for the acceptance of [[Forza Italia]], [[Silvio Berlusconi]]\u2019s party, into the EPP. This was of help to Berlusconi, who went on to win the elections in Italy in 2001. That year Agag intervened in the closing campaign rally of Forza Italia in [[Rome]].\n\nIn 2000 Agag was elected in [[Mexico]] Secretary General of the Christian Democratic International, renamed at that meeting [[Centrist Democrat International|Centrist Democratic International]]. This global political organization has over 90 member parties from all over the world.\n\nIn 2001, Agag made a decision to cease his political activities in order to furtherance a career in business and sporting activities.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} The following year he was succeeded at the [[European People's Party|EPP]] by an old fellow during his times with Aznar: [[Antonio L\u00f3pez-Ist\u00fariz White|Antonio L\u00f3pez-Ist\u00fariz]]. He remained a member of the European Parliament until 2002.<ref name=europarl-agag/>\n\n==Business career==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=October 2019}}\nIn 2002 Agag moved to London and started his own consultancy firm. He has been very active in multiple fields, including telecoms, energy, and especially media. Agag expanded his activities to financial advisory and fund management, forming a company called Addax Capital LLP, which is regulated by the FSA. Agag is currently Chairman of Addax and was joined in 2009 by [[Ignacio Mu\u00f1oz Alonso]], former CEO of [[N M Rothschild & Sons|Rothschild Bank]] in Spain, who worked for [[Lehman Brothers]] before that.\n\nIn 2007, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' named him as one of the 10 \"shakers and movers\" of the Spanish economy, and he was described as a \"political hopeful, economist, banker and indefatigable dealmaker\".\n\nAgag is frequently mentioned in the media for his extensive range of contacts, both political and business, from all over the world. The Spanish newspaper \u2018[[El Pa\u00eds|El Pais]]\u2019 once described his Nokia [[SIM card|SIM Card]] as \"Priceless\".\n\nIn 2008, [[GQ|GQ Magazine]] elected him as the Spanish \"Businessman of the Year.\"\n\n==Sports : Formula 1, Formula E, GP2 and football==\nAgag business activity within sports mainly focuses on motorsport and football. According to the Spanish newspaper \u2018El Pais\u2019, Agag, together with [[Flavio Briatore]], acquired very early on the [[Formula One]] T.V. rights for Spain. This was achieved via a U.K. based company and played a key role in the huge expansion of Formula One in Spain where television audiences have multiplied over the past few years. Agag is also very heavily involved in the \u2018sponsorship\u2019 side of the business, he is said to be behind some of the major deals lately achieved in the sport.<ref>{{cite news| title =El conseguidor| publisher =elpais.com| url =http://www.elpais.com/articulo/reportajes/conseguidor/elpepusocdmg/20070225elpdmgrep_1/Tes| date =25 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Agag, da Aznar alla Formula 1 una nuova vita tra sport e affari| publisher =archiviostorico.corriere.it| url =http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2005/agosto/12/Agag_Aznar_alla_Formula_una_co_8_050812004.shtml| date =12 August 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Who is Alejandro Agag and why does it matter?| publisher =grandprix.com| url =http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19564.html| date =29 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nAgag owns the [[Barwa Addax]] [[GP2 Series]] Team which won the title in 2008 and was runner-up in 2009.<ref>{{cite news| title =Alejandro Agag sabe por d\u00f3nde sopla el viento de la F\u00f3rmula 1| publisher =elconfidencial.com| url =http://www.elconfidencial.com/dentro-del-paddock/alejandro-agag-formula-uno-20100608.html| date =8 June 2010}}</ref> He took over the Team from former F1 driver, [[Adri\u00e1n Campos]], in mid-2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Renamed Addax team sign Grosjean |publisher=autosport.com |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/73447 |date=26 February 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-26 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mqhLkijp?url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/73447 |archivedate=17 January 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The team's main sponsor is the Qatari real estate company, Barwa. Three drivers from Addax, [[Romain Grosjean]], [[Vitaly Petrov]] and [[Lucas di Grassi]], have made it to the F1.<ref>{{cite news| title =Addax Team sees Perez move to F1| publisher =motorsport.com| url =http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=390162&FS=GP2| archive-url =https://archive.is/20120907012445/http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=390162&FS=GP2| url-status =dead| archive-date =7 September 2012| date =6 October 2010}}</ref> In 2010, Agag started competing in GP3 with the Addax GP3 Team.<ref>{{cite news|title=ADDAX TEAM SIGN MEXICAN DRIVER PABLO SANCHEZ FOR GP3 2010 SEASON |publisher=theleader.info |url=http://www.theleader.info/article/21746/spain/national/addax-team-sign-mexican-driver-pablo-sanchez-for-gp3-2010-season/ |date=12 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325064638/http://www.theleader.info/article/21746/spain/national/addax-team-sign-mexican-driver-pablo-sanchez-for-gp3-2010-season/ |archivedate=25 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Alejandro Agag: Basta politica, ora solo corse| publisher =rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it| url =http://rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it/rotta_a_sud_ovest/2010/05/alejandro-agag-basta-politica-ora-solo-corse.html}} {{dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Barwa Campos Team begin season with victory |publisher=gulf-times.com |url=http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=290581&version=1&template_id=49&parent_id=29 |date=14 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515121625/http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=290581&version=1&template_id=49&parent_id=29 |archivedate=15 May 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThrough his connection within sport, Agag has formed friendships with [[Flavio Briatore]], [[Bernie Ecclestone]] and [[Lakshmi Mittal]].<ref>{{cite news| title =Alejandro Agag es ya uno de los grandes empresarios de la F\u00f3rmula 1 de la mano de Flavio Briatore| publisher =elmundo.es| url =http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2005/08/11/espana/1123720238.html| date =11 August 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =Alejandro Agag says no to Bernie Ecclestone| publisher =duemotori.com| url =http://www.duemotori.com/news/f1/24255_Alejandro_Agag_says_no_to_Bernie_Ecclestone.php| date =28 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alejandro Agag, dopo Bernie Ecclestone? |publisher=rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it |url=http://rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it/rotta_a_sud_ovest/2007/02/alejandro_agag_.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510130320/http://rottasudovest.blog.lastampa.it/rotta_a_sud_ovest/2007/02/alejandro_agag_.html |archivedate=10 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alejandro Agag: \"He visto a muchos ricos arruinarse con la F1\" |publisher=intereconomia.com |url=http://www.intereconomia.com/noticias/alejandro-agag-%E2%80%9Che-visto-muchos-ricos-arruinarse-f1%E2%80%9D |date=8 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717185620/http://www.intereconomia.com/noticias/alejandro-agag-%E2%80%9Che-visto-muchos-ricos-arruinarse-f1%E2%80%9D |archivedate=17 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Together, they bought the English football club [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=QPR football club recommends 1p/shr offer from Flavio Briatore's Sarita Capital |publisher=abcmoney.co.uk |url=http://www.abcmoney.co.uk/news/032007127826.htm |date=3 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100416070915/http://www.abcmoney.co.uk/news/032007127826.htm |archivedate=16 April 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAgag served as chairman of QPR for a few months during the take-over then remained in the Club as a shareholder. The plan was to have QPR promoted to the English Premier League, a feat that was achieved in 2011.<ref>{{cite news| title =QPR tycoons hesitate on spending spree | publisher =telegraph.co.uk| url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2288449/QPR-tycoons-hesitate-on-spending-spree.html| date =10 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/may/07/qpr-leeds-united-championship | title=Joy and relief for QPR after FA clear the path to promotion  | date=7 May 2011 | first=John | last=Ashdown | newspaper=The Guardian | accessdate=12 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHe is currently in charge of the [[FIA Formula E Championship|Formula E Championship]], an electric car racing series. The [[2014\u201315 Formula E season|inaugural season]] began on September 2014 and lasted until June 2015. Formula E Holdings, whose CEO is Alejandro Agag, has set up races in ten different cities around the world which are [[Beijing ePrix|Beijing]], [[Putrajaya ePrix|Putrajaya]], [[Punta del Este ePrix|Punta del Este]], [[Buenos Aires ePrix|Buenos Aires]], [[Miami ePrix|Miami]], [[Long Beach ePrix|Long Beach]], [[Monaco ePrix|Monaco]], [[Berlin ePrix|Berlin]], [[Moscow ePrix|Moscow]] and [[London ePrix|London]].<ref name=cities>[http://www.fiaformulae.com/en/calendar.aspx \u00abFormula E's calendar\u00bb] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228002842/http://www.fiaformulae.com/en/calendar.aspx |date=28 December 2014 }}. date =12 August 2014.</ref> The races take place in [[street circuit]]s and began in Beijing on 13 September 2014.<ref name=Beijing>[http://www.formulaegreen.com/2014/05/19/calendario-del-campeonato-de-formula-e-2014-2015-estas-preparado/ \u00abFormula E's beginning\u00bb] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140812102008/http://www.formulaegreen.com/2014/05/19/calendario-del-campeonato-de-formula-e-2014-2015-estas-preparado/ |date=12 August 2014 }}. date =12 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 5 September 2002, Agag married Ana Aznar Botella, the daughter of then Prime Minister [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aznar]] and politician [[Ana Botella]], at [[El Escorial]] in Madrid. Guests included King [[Juan Carlos I]] and Queen [[Sofia of Spain]]. British Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] and Italian Prime Minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]] served as witnesses.<ref name=euobserver-20020907>{{cite news |url=https://euobserver.com/political/7474 |title=Spanish wedding turned into a political affair |last=Spinant |first=Daniela |website=EUobserver |date=7 September 2002 |accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=bbc-20020905>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/2239721.stm |title=In pictures: Aznar's daughter marries |work=BBC News |date=5 September 2002 |accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite conference | author = Alejandro Agag | author2 = Group of the European People's Party (Christian Democrats) and European Democrats in the EU Parliament. | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=DRC3xZlEMcYC&pg=PA3 | title = The future of the European people's party | conference = Our vision of Europe : proximity, competitiveness and visibility. | via = [http://archive.is/4pCuE/ archive.is] | isbn = 9789044111804 | location = Leuvent | publisher = Garant | year = 2001 | pages = 239\u2013242 | oclc = 912254670}}<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=OEZ-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236 | title = international bibliography for the political science | page = 236 | chapter = Bibliography for 2002 | author = British Library of Political and Economic Science - Routledge | publisher = Routledge | volume = 51 | date = March 10, 2004 | isbn = 9781134339969 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190830165307/https://books.google.it/books?id=OEZ-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236&dq=%22Our+vision+of+Europe+:+proximity,+competitiveness+and+visibility.%22&source=bl&ots=tDAP53H2Qb&sig=ACfU3U2RJcCN0QZSGMpm1VzyrxrLOpysWQ&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjq89WWh6vkAhVLiqQKHSZ2AdY4ChDoATAAegQICRAB%23v=onepage&q=%22Our%20vision%20of%20Europe%20:%20proximity,%20competitiveness%20and%20visibility.%22&f=false | archive-date = 30 August 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 30 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{commons category|Alejandro Agag}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agag, Alejandro}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Madrid]]\n[[Category:People's Party (Spain) politicians]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Algerian descent]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Auto racing executives]]\n[[Category:Formula E people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Philcroix91", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Removed CV-styled self celebr.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alejandro_Agag"}
